n{{Refend}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fordham.edu/halsall/basis/columban.asp The Life of St. Columban, by the Monk Jonas] ([[Internet History Sourcebooks Project|Internet Medieval Sourcebook]])\n* {{CathEncy|wstitle=St. Columbanus|short=x}}\n* {{Cite NIE|wstitle=Columban, Saint|short=x}}\n* [http://www.knightsofstcolumbanus.ie/ The Order of the Knights of Saint Columbanus]\n* [https://celt.ucc.ie//published/T201053/index.html Sermons of Columbanus] ([[Corpus of Electronic Texts|CELT]])\n* [https://celt.ucc.ie/published/T201054/index.html Letters of Columbanus] (CELT)\n\n{{Hiberno-Latin authors}}\n{{Canonization}}\n{{Subject bar |portal1= Biography |portal2= Catholicism |portal3= Ireland}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Irish writers]]\n[[Category:Irish literature]]\n[[Category:6th-century Latin writers]]\n[[Category:7th-century Latin writers]]\n[[Category:543 births]]\n[[Category:615 deaths]]\n[[Category:Irish Christian missionaries]]\n[[Category:Founders of Catholic religious communities]]\n[[Category:7th-century Christian saints]]\n[[Category:Burials at Bobbio Abbey]]\n[[Category:6th-century Christians]]\n[[Category:Medieval Irish saints]]\n[[Category:6th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:7th-century Irish people]]\n[[Category:People from County Meath]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in France]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:Medieval Irish saints on the Continent]]\n[[Category:Medieval Irish writers]]\n[[Category:Founders of Christian monasteries]]\n[[Category:7th-century Irish writers]]\n[[Category:6th-century Irish writers]]\n[[Category:Latinists]]\n", "name_user": "104.231.14.57", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Columbanus"}
{"title_page": "Carlsberg Group", "text_new": "{{short description|Danish brewery group}}\n{{distinguish|Karlsberg (brewery)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name  =  Carlsberg A/S\n| logo  = Carlsberg Group logo.svg\n| type  = [[Aktieselskab]]\n| traded_as  = {{OMX|CSE1595|CARL A}}, {{OMXb|CSE1596|CARL B}}\n| area_served        = Worldwide\n| founder = [[J. C. Jacobsen]]\n| key_people  = [[Cees 't Hart]] <small>(President and [[chief executive officer|CEO]])</small>, [[Flemming Besenbacher]] <small>([[Chairman]])</small>\n| industry  = [[Beverages]]\n| products  = [[Beer]]s, [[cider]]s, [[soft drink]]s, [[bottled water]]\n| brands  =  Carlsberg, [[Tuborg]], [[Kronenbourg 1664]], [[Baltika]], [[Grimbergen (beer)|Grimbergen]], [[Somersby cider|Somersby]]\n| revenue  = [[Danish krone|DKK]] 62.6 billion ($9.48 billion) <small>(2016)</small><ref name=\"AR2016\">{{cite web |url=https://carlsberggroup.com/media/10899/carlsberg-group-annual-report-2016.pdf |title=Annual Report 2016}}</ref>\n| profit  =  DKK 8.2 billion ($1.24 billion) <small>(2016)</small><ref name=\"AR2016\" />\n| num_employees  = 41,000 <small>([[full-time equivalent|FTE]], average 2016)</small><ref name=\"AR2016\" />\n| homepage  =  [http://www.carlsberggroup.com/ www.carlsberggroup.com]\n| foundation  =  {{Start date and age|1847}}\n| location  =   [[Copenhagen]], Denmark\n}}\n'''Carlsberg A/S''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|\u0251\u02d0r|l|z|b|\u025c\u02d0r|\u0261}}; {{IPA-da|\u02c8k\u02b0\u0251\u02c0ls\u02ccp\u025b\u0250\u032f\u02c0|lang}}) is a Danish multinational brewer. Founded in 1847 by [[J. C. Jacobsen]], the company's headquarters is located in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. Since Jacobsen's death in 1887, the majority owner of the company has been the [[Carlsberg Foundation]]. The company's flagship brand is [[#Carlsberg|Carlsberg]] (named after Jacobsen's son [[Carl Jacobsen|Carl]]). It also brews [[Tuborg]], [[Kronenbourg]], [[Somersby cider]], Russia's best-selling beer [[Baltika]], Belgian [[Grimbergen (beer)|Grimbergen]] abbey beers, and more than 500 local beers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/brands/Pages/Default.aspx |title=Carlsberg \u2013 Brands home<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=19 March 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207204742/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/brands/Pages/Default.aspx |archive-date=7 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe company employs around 41,000 people, primarily located in Western Europe, Eastern Europe and Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carlsberggroup.com/media/10899/carlsberg-group-annual-report-2016.pdf|title=Carlsberg Group Annual Report 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:J C Jacobsen.jpg|thumb|J.C. Jacobsen standing in his winter garden known as ''[[Carlsberg (district)#Carlsberg Academy|Pompeji]]'', next to a table with laboratory equipment, a bottle of lager, a beer glass, and books by [[Louis Pasteur]] and [[Emil Christian Hansen]]. Painting by [[August Jerndorff]] (1886)]] \n[[Image:EXPO 1885 Carlsberg.jpg|thumb|Diplome d'Honneur Antwerp 1885 expo]]\nCarlsberg was founded by [[J. C. Jacobsen]], a [[philanthropist]] and avid art collector. With his fortune he amassed an art collection which is housed in the [[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek]] in central Copenhagen. The first brew was finished on 10 November 1847, and the export of Carlsberg beer began in 1868 with the export of one barrel to [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]].<ref name=\"Carl\">{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberguk.co.uk/AboutUs/heritage/Pages/Global.aspx | title=Carlsberg Group - Our Heritage | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Some of the company's original logos include an elephant, after which some of its lagers are named, and the [[swastika]], the use of which was discontinued in the 1930s because of its association with political parties in neighboring Germany.\n\nJacobsen's son Carl opened a brewery in 1882 named Ny (New) Carlsberg forcing him to rename his brewery Gamle (Old) Carlsberg. The companies were merged and run under Carl's direction in 1906 and remained so until his death in 1914.<ref name=\"Carl\"/>\n\nJacobsen set up the [[Carlsberg Laboratory]] in 1875, which worked on scientific problems related to brewing. It featured a Department of Chemistry and a Department of Physiology. The species of yeast used to make [[pale lager]], ''[[Saccharomyces carlsbergensis]]'', was isolated by Emil Christian Hansen at the laboratory in 1883 and bears its name; this was shared freely by Carlsberg.<ref name=\"Carl\"/> The Carlsberg Laboratory also developed the concept of [[pH]] and made advances in protein chemistry.<ref name=euchems>{{cite web|url=http://www.euchems.org/Distinguished/20thCentury/sorensen.asp|title=S\u00f8rensen, S\u00f8ren Peter Lauritz (1868\u20131939)|accessdate=9 January 2007|work=100 Distinguished European Chemists|publisher=European Association for Chemical and Molecular Sciences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061004013146/http://www.euchems.org/Distinguished/20thCentury/sorensen.asp|archive-date=4 October 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1972, the Carlsberg Research Centre was established and the Carlsberg Laboratory is an independent unit of the Centre.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsbergfondet.dk/en/Afdelinger/Carlsberg%20Laboratorium.aspx | title=The Carlssberg Laboratory | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1876, J.C. Jacobsen established the Carlsberg Foundation, run by trustees from the Royal Danish Academy of Sciences and Letters,  which managed the Carlsberg Laboratory as well as supporting scientific research within the fields of natural sciences, mathematics, philosophy, the humanities and social sciences in Denmark. Because of a conflict with his son Carl, Jacobsen's brewery was left to the Foundation upon his death in 1887.<ref name=\"The Carlsberg Foundation\">{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Company/Foundations/CARLSBERGFOUNDATION/Pages/Default.aspx | title=The Carlsberg Foundation | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first overseas license for brewing was given to the Photos Photiades Breweries, and in 1966 Carlsberg beer was brewed for the first time outside Denmark at the Photiades breweries in Cyprus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carlsberggroup.com/who-we-are/about-the-carlsberg-group/our-rich-heritage/|title=Who we are \" About the Carlsberg Group \" Our Rich Heritage \" Carlsberg Group|website=Carlsberg Group|language=en|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref> The first brewery to be built outside Denmark was in [[Blantyre|Blantyre, Malawi]] in 1968.<ref name=\"Carl\"/>\n\nCarlsberg merged with Tuborg breweries in 1970 forming the United Breweries AS, and merged with [[Tetley's (beer)|Tetley]] in 1992. Carlsberg became the sole owner of Carlsberg-Tetley in 1997.<ref name=\"Carl\"/>\n\nIn 2008 Carlsberg Group, together with [[Heineken International|Heineken]], bought [[Scottish & Newcastle]], the largest brewer in the UK, for \u00a37.8bn ($15.3bn).<ref name=BBCJan2508>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7208341.stm |title=Brewer S&N agrees \u00a37.8bn takeover |author= |date=25 January 2008 |publisher=BBC }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 the company joined leading alcohol producers as part of a [[International Alliance for Responsible Drinking|producers' commitments]] to reducing harmful drinking.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Home {{!}} Producers' Commitments|url = http://www.producerscommitments.org/|website = Producers' Commitments|accessdate = 2015-12-23|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Carlsberg agreed to take over [[Greece]]'s third largest brewery, the [[Olympic Brewery]], adding to its operations in the country already and effectively transforming the firm into the second biggest market player in Greece.<ref>{{cite press release | publisher=Reuters| date=18 November 2014| title=Carlsberg becomes no.2 in Greece with Olympic Brewery takeover | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/18/us-carlsberg-greece-idUSKCN0J20KY20141118}}</ref>\n\nThe old brewery in Copenhagen is open for tours.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.visitcarlsberg.com/#the-flow | title=Visit Carlsberg | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> In January 2020 The Brewery Tour is closed for a complete refurbishment. it is not known when it will reopen <ref>C</ref>Carlsberg website\n\n== Regional operations ==\nThe Carlsberg Group divides their operations into three market areas: Northern and Western Europe, Eastern Europe and Asia.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.carlsberggroup.com/investor/companyprofile/Pages/default.aspx |title=Carlsberg Group - Company Profile  |work=carlsberggroup.com |year=2012 |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Eastern Europe ===\n[[Baltic Beverages Holding]] is owned by Carlsberg. Previously, it was a joint venture between Carlsberg and [[Scottish & Newcastle]] in Russia.<ref name=BBCJan2508/> The company is a significant operator in the brewing industry in Russia, [[Ukraine]], the [[Baltic countries]], [[Kazakhstan]] and [[Uzbekistan]]. It has a majority interest in [[Baltika Breweries|OAO Baltika Breweries]], the largest brewery in the [[Russian Federation]] and [[Eastern Europe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/ee/Pages/Russia.aspx |title=Russia - Baltika Breweries |publisher=Carlsberg Group }}</ref>\n\nThe Uzbek government claimed the subsidiary owed $4.6 million in taxes from unreported revenue. Lower courts also claimed that Carlsberg illegally produced 1.6 million litres of beer from 2008 to 2010. For these reasons, in March 2012, Carlsberg suspended production at its Uzbek plant and asked its employees to take an unpaid leave.<ref>{{cite news|title=Uzbek Court Rules Against Carlsberg Subsidiary|url=http://www.satrapia.com/news/article/uzbek-court-rules-against-carlsberg-subsidiary/|newspaper=The Gazette of Central Asia|date=20 October 2012|publisher=Satrapia}}</ref> In late 2012, the Uzbek Court declined Carlsberg's tax appeal.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://enews.fergananews.com/news.php?id=2389&mode=snews | title=Uzbekistan: Court declined tax appeal by Carlsberg Uzbekistan | publisher=Ferghana News Agency | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> Production resumed in April 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/uzbekistan-central-asias-poisoned-chalice/483598.html | title=Uzbekistan, Central Asia's Poisoned Chalice | newspaper=Moscow Times | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> The brewery produces 1.3 million litres of beer under three local brands Sarbast Original, Sarbast Extra, and Sarbast Special, plus the international brand Tuborg Green.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/ee/Pages/Uzbekistan.aspx | title=Carslberg Group - Uzbekistan | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Northern and Western Europe ===\nCarlsberg acquired the [[Aldaris Brewery]] in Riga, [[Latvia]], in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/NWE/Pages/Latvia.aspx |title=Carlsberg Group - Latvia |work=carlsberggroup.com |year=2012 |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> The brewery was founded in 1865, and produces Aldaris brand beers.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ratebeer.com/brewers//aldaris-carlsberg/852/ |title=Aldaris (Carlsberg) - RateBeer |work=ratebeer.com |year=2012 |quote=Aldaris |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Carlsberg Polska]] is the Polish subsidiary of the Carlsberg Group. Carlsberg acquired 100% control of the Okocim Group, which included the [[Okocim Brewery]], in 2004. The [[subsidiary]] owns four [[brewing plant]]s and employs a staff of 1,250. It is the third largest brewing company in [[Poland]] with a 14.4% [[market share]].<ref>[http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Company/Markets/Pages/Poland.aspx Carlsberg \u2013 Poland] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327113235/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Company/Markets/Pages/Poland.aspx |date=27 March 2010 }}</ref> Brands include Harna\u015b, [[Carlsberg Polska#Kasztelan Brewery|Kasztelan]], [[Okocim Brewery|Okocim]], [[Piast Brewery|Piast]], Somersby and Carlsberg.\n\nCarlsberg Sweden (Sverige) is based in [[Stockholm]], and owns the [[Falcon Brewery]] in [[Falkenberg]], and the [[Raml\u00f6sa]] mineral water bottling facility in [[Helsingborg]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/NWE/Pages/Sweden.aspx |title=Carlsberg Group - Sweden |work=carlsberggroup.com |year=2012 |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> Carnegie Porter, a 5.5% abv [[Baltic porter]], along with the [[Pripps]] and Falcon brand lagers, are brewed in Falkenberg.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ratebeer.com/brewer/765/sort/0/ |title=Carlsberg Sverige - RateBeer |work=ratebeer.com |year=2012 |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nNorway brands include: Arendals, [[E. C. Dahls Brewery|Dahls]], [[Frydenlund]], Nordlands, [[Ringnes]] and [[Tou (brewery)|Tou]].\n\nOther European brands include: [[Birrificio Angelo Poretti]] (Italy), [[Feldschl\u00f6sschen]] (Switzerland), [[Holsten]] (Germany), [[Jacobsen (beer)|Jacobsen]], [[Karhu (beer)|Karhu]] (Finland), [[Kronenbourg]] (France), [[Super Bock]] (Portugal) and [[Tetley's (beer)|Tetley]] (UK).\nA result of the take over of [[Scottish & Newcastle]], Carlsberg controls the [[San Miguel Corporation|San Miguel]] brand in the UK.\n\n===North America===\nIn the US, the Carlsberg group brands are distributed by St. Killian Import Co., based in Everett, Massachusetts, importing Carlsberg beer directly from Denmark. Brands that are imported include: Carlsberg Beer (bottles and kegs), Carlsberg Elephant, Kronenbourg 1664, Grimbergen, Tetley's English Ale, Okocim.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Carlsberg Group - USA|url = http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/ExLid/Pages/USA.aspx|website = www.carlsberggroup.com|accessdate = 2015-11-16}}</ref>\n\nCarlsberg was brewed in Canada by [[Canadian Breweries]]/[[Carling O'Keefe]] beginning in 1972.<ref>https://justbeerapp.com/brand/carlsberg-group-1</ref> After Carling O'Keefe was merged with Molsons, Carlsberg opened its own brewery. Since 2008, Carlsberg no longer brews Carlsberg in Canada, instead, it imports Carlsberg along with its other brands.\n\n=== Asia ===\n====East Asia====\nCarlsberg started to export beer to [[China]] in 1876.<ref name=CarlsberginChina/> In the late 1990s, Carlsberg had two breweries in China \u2013 [[Huizhou]] and [[Shanghai]]. The company acquired Huizhou Brewery in [[Guangdong]] Province in 1995, which started to supply both the mainland Chinese and [[Hong Kong]] market.<ref name=CarlsberginChina>{{cite journal|title=Carlsberg in China |url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/investor/downloadcentre/Documents/Other%20Presentations/27.11.06%20Carlsberg%20in%20China%20.pdf |date=27 November 2006 |publisher=Carlsberg }}</ref> Carlsberg invested around US$30 million in its Shanghai brewery, and started production in 1998. In 2000, Carlsberg sold a majority stake in its Shanghai brewery to [[Tsingtao Brewery]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Carlsberg sells majority stake in Chinese brewery |url=http://www.brandrepublic.com/news/11369/Carlsberg-sells-majority-stake-Chinese-brewery/ |date=10 August 2000 |author=Camilla Palmer |publisher=Brand Republic }}</ref> Carlsberg formerly had a brewery in [[Tai Po]], Hong Kong, which was established in 1981, but shut it down in 1999<ref name=CarlsbergChina/> due to high costs.\n\nIn 2003, Carlsberg acquired the Kunming Brewery and the Dali Brewery in [[Yunnan]] province. At the time, the Dali Brewery was the largest beer brewery in Yunnan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Carlsberg Asia acquired second brewery in the Yunnan province, China |url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/investor/news/Pages/carlsbergasiaacquiressecondbreweryintheyunnanprov-HQ2003.aspx |date=6 October 2003 |publisher=Carlsberg }}</ref> In 2004, Carlsberg became a major shareholder in Lhasa Brewery in the [[Tibet Autonomous Region]]. At 3,700 metres above sea level, Lhasa Brewery is believed to be the highest altitude brewery in the Carlsberg Group.<ref name=CarlsbergChina>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/asia/Pages/China.aspx |title=Carlsberg China}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Carlsberg sold its remaining interest in the Shanghai brewery to Tsingtao Brewery.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2008-09/11/content_7017885.htm |title=Tsingtao snaps up brewery |date=11 September 2008 |author=Zhou Yan |newspaper=China Daily }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2011, Carlsberg announced a new joint venture with Chongqing Brewery and Chongqing Light Textile Holding. Chongqing Light Textile Holding is a major shareholder of Chongqing Brewery. The joint venture, to be called Chongqing Xinghui Investment Co., Ltd, would operate twelve breweries in China in [[Chongqing]], [[Sichuan]], [[Guangxi]], [[Guizhou]] and [[Hunan]]. Chongqing Brewery would contribute five breweries and Chongqing Light Textile Holding would contribute seven breweries to the joint venture. Carlsberg would inject 160 million [[Danish crowns]] (about US$30.90 million) and have a 30% interest in the venture.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/01/carlsberg-china-venture-idUSLDE77013320110801 |title=Carlsberg says to own 30 pct of new China venture |date=1 August 2011 |author=John Acher |work=Reuters }}</ref>\n\nCarlsberg also owns Wusu Beer Group in [[Urumqi]], [[Xinjiang]] in Northwest China.\n\n====South Asia====\nCarlsberg India Pvt. Ltd. headquartered in Gurgaon, India is a foreign direct investment company formed to brew and market Carlsberg beer in India. The company has also brought the Tuborg and Palone brands to India. Palone is sold as a 'strong' beer with 7.5% alcohol by volume. Strong beers dominate the Indian market, estimated in 2008 to total approximately 17 million hectolitres with over a 72% share. Carlsberg is available in most states of India, with five operational breweries in: Alwar (Rajasthan), Aurangabad (Maharashtra) both of which started in the summer of 2008, the former Hacke-Beck brewery in Paonta Sahib (Himachal Pradesh) where brewing commenced in July 2007, Kolkata (West Bengal) opened in September 2009, Patna Brewery (Patna) opened for brewing in 2014, Dharuhera Brewery opened on 7 May 2013, and Hyderabad (Telangana) opened in December 2010. Carlsberg India Pvt. Ltd. currently employs over 700 people and is headed by Michael Norgaard Jensen, Managing Director.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsbergindia.com/company/MD_message/Pages/MD'sMessage.aspx | title=Managing Director's Message | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Southeast Asia====\nCarlsberg Brewery Malaysia Berhad (Carlsberg Malaysia) was incorporated in December 1969, and began brewing Carlsberg Green Label locally in 1972. It is located in [[Petaling Jaya]], [[Selangor]]. Since then, the brand has become one of the leading beer brands with more than a 50% share of the Malaysian market. It manufactures and distribute beer, stout and other beverages mainly in the domestic market and has investments in Sri Lanka, Singapore and in a Malaysian alcoholic beverage company. Brands under Carlsberg Malaysia include: Carlsberg Green Label, Carlsberg Smooth Draught, Carlsberg Special Brew, Kronenbourg 1664 Blanc, Asahi Super Dry, Somersby Apple Cider, SKOL beer, Danish Royal Stout, Corona Extra, Jolly Shandy Lemon and as well as non-alcoholic Nutrimalt drink. In addition, Carlsberg Malaysia through its subsidiaries, has a wide range of imported international beer brands including Hoegaarden, Stella Artois, Budweiser, Grimbergen and Beck\u2019s. However CBMB sold off their subsidiaries and focus to grow Carlsberg Group brand.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsbergmalaysia.com.my/web/company/cm_carlsbergmsia.aspx | title=Carlsberg Malaysia | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Carlsberg announced the formation of a joint venture with the Myanmar Golden Star (MGS) group to establish a beer production facility in the Bago Industrial Zone, about an hour's drive from [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]]. Carlsberg will hold a majority 51 per cent stake in the venture and will provide seed capital in the range of $35 million to $50 million, with construction slated to commence in February.<ref name=burmanew>\n{{Cite news\n| title = Carlsberg takes a sip in Myanmar\n| publisher = Investvine.com\n| date = 1 February 2013\n| url= http://investvine.com/carlsberg-takes-a-sip-in-myanmar/\n| accessdate =14 February 2013}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Singha]] beer began being produced by Carlsberg's Russian plant for distribution in European markets in March 2013.<ref name=ref2013021407>\n    {{Cite news\n    | title = Singha starts roll-out in Asia and Europe\n    | publisher = Investvine.com\n    | date = 14 February 2013\n    | url= http://investvine.com/singha-starts-roll-out-in-asia-and-europe/\n    | accessdate =3 April 2013}}\n</ref> \n\nOther Southeast Asian brands include Halida Beer (Vietnam).\n\n====West Asia====\nIn [[Israel]], the [[Israel Beer Breweries]] in [[Ashkelon]] produces Carlsberg and [[Tuborg Brewery|Tuborg]]. Carlsberg and Tuborg were launched on the Israeli market in 1992. Initially they were imported from Copenhagen, but in 1995 local production began at a greenfield brewery. The brewery is situated above a large underground aquifer<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/ExLid/Pages/Israel.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=30 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130125111124/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/ExLid/Pages/Israel.aspx |archive-date=25 January 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Beers ==\n\n=== Carlsberg{{anchor|Carlsberg Beer|Carlsberg Lager|Carlsberg Pilsner}} ===\n\n[[Image:33 cl Carlsberg beer bottle.png|thumb|100px|upright|A 33cl Carlsberg profile bottle]]\n\nCarlsberg is the flagship beer brand in Carlsberg Group's portfolio of 155 brands. It is a 5% abv [[pilsner]] beer (3.8% in the UK and branded as Carlsberg Danish Pilsener) with a global distribution to 140 markets.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/brands/Pages/carlsberg.aspx\n| title=Carlsberg beer product information\n| publisher=www.carlsberggroup.com\n| accessdate=4 March 2014\n| last=\n| first=\n}}</ref> \nIt is also known as Carlsberg Lager, Carlsberg Beer and Carlsberg Pilsner. It was first brewed in 1904,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/brands/Pages/CarlsbergPilsner.aspx |title=Carlsberg Group \u2013 Carlsberg Pilsner |publisher=www.carlsberggroup.com |accessdate=21 October 2009 }}</ref> and was created by [[Carl Jacobsen]], son of Carlsberg's founder [[JC Jacobsen]].\n\nThe introduction of the Carlsberg pilsner also saw the reintroduction of the [[Art Nouveau]]-style logo that has been used nearly unmodified since 1904, and later became the logo of the entire company. It was designed by [[Thorvald Bindesb\u00f8ll]].<ref name=\"Carl\"/>\n\nIn Denmark the beer is often known as ''Hof'' ([[Noble court|court]]) due to its [[Royal warrant of appointment|Royal Warrant]]. This nickname was adopted into the brand in 1931 but discontinued in Denmark in 1991. The term is still used in other markets such as the UK and Sweden.<ref>[http://www.carlsbergsverige.se/Drycker/ol/Sidor/CarlsbergHof.aspx Carlsbergsverige.se - Carlsberg Hof]</ref>\n\n=== Special Brew ===\n{{Redirect|Special Brew|the ska song of the same name|Special Brew (song)}}<!-- Redirect is to this specific subsection -->\n\nSpecial Brew is a [[strong lager]] brewed only in Denmark and the United Kingdom. It was initially brewed by Carlsberg to commemorate a visit to Denmark by [[Winston Churchill]] in 1950.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/brands/Pages/Carlsbergspecialbrew.aspx |title=Carlsberg Group \u2013 Carlsberg Special Brew |publisher=www.carlsberggroup.com |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> The flavour incorporates \"cognac flavours among its tasting notes\" as Churchill was partial to brandy. In May 1951 two crates were delivered to Churchill's London home. In a thank-you letter Churchill called the drink \"Commemoration Lager\". In Denmark the drink was called {{lang|da|P\u00e5skebryg}}&nbsp;(\"Easter Brew\"), but the Easter Brew has since been replaced by a weaker beer ({{lang|da|Carls P\u00e5ske}}). For the British market Carlsberg called the drink Special Brew, and production was started in [[Northampton]] in the 1950s.\n\nAt 7.5% alcohol (previously 9%, then 8% for a short time), Special Brew is part of a group of strong lagers that are termed \"super-strength\" in the UK and [[malt liquor]] in the USA. This beer is often associated with street alcoholics.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2005/oct/03/drugsandalcohol.homelessness | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Matthew | last=Weaver | title=Call for ban on super-strength 'tramp juice' | date=3 October 2005}}</ref>\n\nA single can (440mL) of Special Brew contains 3.5 [[Unit of alcohol|units of alcohol]] (previously 4.5 units) whilst the maximum recommended daily intake for a man is two units. In January 2015, it was reported that Carlsberg would reduce the units per can to less than four, in line with a UK government pledge that no single can should contain more than four units. The change, a reduction either in the size of the can from 500mL to 440mL, or the alcoholic strength of the beer, was considered for implementation in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-magazine-monitor-30795336 |title=The secret history of Special Brew |publisher=BBC |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> Both changes were made; the cans have since been reduced to 440 mL, and the ABV reduced from 9% to 8%, then another drop to 7.5%.\n\n=== Elephant beer ===\n[[Image:Elefantporten (Carlsberg).jpg|thumb|200px|The [[Elephant Gate and Tower, Carlsberg|Elephant Gate]] in Copenhagen, Denmark]] \n[[Image:Carlsberg Elephant Beer.jpg|thumb|upright|50px|Elephant beer]]\nIn 1901, at brewer Carl Jacobsen's initiative, the Architect Professor J. L. Dahlerup created a tower resting on four elephants carved in granite from the Danish island of [[Bornholm]]. Jacobsen's inspiration was the obelisk supporting an elephant on the [[Piazza della Minerva]] in Rome.<ref>[http://www.visitcarlsberg.dk/history/Footprints/Valby/Pages/TheElephantTower.aspx Visit Carlsberg]</ref> The four elephants each bear the initial of one of Carl Jacobsen's children: Theodora, Paula, Helge and Vagn. This became known as The Elephant Gate and is a landmark entrance to the brewery.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} \n\nTo the west of the gate, Carl Jacobsen's motto was inscribed: Laboremus pro Patria (Let us work for our country). Since then, the Elephant has been a famous part of the Carlsberg family, especially after the strong Elephant Beer was created in 1955 under the name Export Lager Beer featuring the Elephant label. The Elephant is still brewed in Carlsberg Breweries in Copenhagen and exported around the world. A few markets brew their own Carlsberg Elephant beer locally according to the original recipe.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nGazza was on to something, this is a good beer\n\n===Other brands in Carlsberg Group's portfolio===\n{{div col}}\n* [[Tuborg]] (International)\n* [[Somersby cider]]s (International)\n* [[Kronenbourg]] / 1664 (International)\n* [[Grimbergen (beer)|Grimbergen]] (International)\n* [[Holsten Brewery|Holsten]] (International)\n* [[Baltika]] (Russia)\n* [[Carlsberg Polska#Bosman Brewery|Bosman]]  (Poland)\n* [[Dali Beer]] (China) \n* [[Feldschl\u00f6sschen]] ([[Switzerland]])\n* [[Gorkha Beer]]  ([[Nepal]])\n* [[Jacobsen (beer)|Jacobsen]] ([[Nordic countries]])\n* [[Lav pivo|Lav]] ([[Serbia]])\n* [[Lao Brewery Company|Beerlao]] ([[Laos]])\n* [[Lvivske]] ([[Ukraine]])\n* [[Mythos Brewery|Mythos]] ([[Greece]])\n* [[Fix (beer)|FIX Hellas]] ([[Greece]])\n* [[Pan (beer)|Pan]] ([[Croatia]])\n* [[Pirinsko]] ([[Bulgaria]])\n* Ringnes (Norway)\n* [[Saku (beer)|Saku]] ([[Estonia]])\n* Sarbast ([[Uzbekistan]])\n* [[Semper Ardens]] ([[Denmark]])\n* [[Shumensko]] ([[Bulgaria]])\n* [[Slavutych Brewery|Slavutych]] ([[Ukraine]])\n* [[Super Bock]] ([[Portugal]])\n* [[\u0160vyturys]] ([[Lithuania]])\n* [[Wusu]] (China)\n* Wiibroe (Denmark)\n{{div col end}}\n[[Image:Carlsberg beers.jpg|thumb|Carlsberg beers]]\nIn total, Carlsberg Group brews more than 500 different beers.\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20120207204742/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/brands/Pages/Default.aspx A selection of brands brewed by breweries owned by Carlsberg Group.]\n\n== Visitors Centre ==\nThe Carlsberg Visitors Centre is located at 11 Gamle Carlsberg Vej, 2500 [[Valby]], [[Denmark]] at the location of the first Carlsberg Brewery. In the courtyard is a smaller replica of the [[The Little Mermaid (statue)|Little Mermaid Statue]] that [[Carl Jacobsen]] donated to [[Copenhagen]]. Also located in connection with the Carlsberg visitors Centre is the Jacobsen House Brewery, a micro brewery creating the Jacobsen speciality range of hand-crafted beers.<ref>[http://www.jacobsenbryg.dk/home/index.htm][http://www.visitcarlsberg.dk/Pages/default.aspx] dead links</ref>\nThe entry ticket includes a free drink at the bar. Visit Carlsberg is located a five-minute walk from the Carlsberg train station.<ref>[http://www.visitcopenhagen.com/content/tourist/what_to_see_and_do/inspiration/top_10_alternative/carlsberg_brewery Carlsberg Brewery www.visitcopenhagen.com]</ref>\n\n== Advertising ==\n[[File:2013 Woodstock 111 Carlsberg.jpg|thumb|Carlsberg advertising at [[Woodstock Festival (Poland)]].]]\nCarlsberg's tagline \"Probably the best lager in the world\" was created in 1973 by Tony Bodinetz at KMP for the UK market.<ref>{{LinkedIn URL | https://www.linkedin.com/in/tony-bodinetz-99408381 | Tony Bodinetz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Foster |first1=Stephen |title=Carlsberg enlists Belgian bikers in great beer battle |url=https://www.moreaboutadvertising.com/2011/10/carlsberg-enlists-belgian-bikers-in-great-beer-battle/ |website=More About Advertising |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> It began to appear in company corporate ads around the world from the 1980s onwards until it was replaced in 2011 in most regions by new tagline \"That calls for a Carlsberg\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/jorgen-rasmussen-right-time-for-change-of-tactics-probably-6273789.html|title= Jorgen Rasmussen: Right time for change of tactics? Probably...|date=8 December 2011|work=The Independent|accessdate=5 April 2013|location=London|first=James|last=Thompson}}</ref>\nThe voice over for the original ad in 1983 was voiced by actor [[Orson Welles]],<ref>http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Company/Timeline/Pages/History.aspx  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213062037/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Company/Timeline/Pages/History.aspx |date=13 February 2008 }}</ref> his voice has been used repeatedly over the years. Welles was not expensive and he liked the advertisements, so he kept his fees to a minimum. In some countries the tagline has been adapted to \"Probably the best beer in the world\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Stamp|first=Gavin|title=Probably the best corporate slogan...|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/5036084.stm|accessdate=17 January 2015|work=BBC News|date=18 June 2006}}</ref>\n\nCarlsberg was featured in the film ''[[Ice Cold in Alex]]'' (not, however, in the book on which the film was based) as the lager the main cast get to drink after driving across the desert. Lines from the film gave rise to one of Carlsberg's best known advertising slogans in the UK: \"worth waiting for\".\n\nCarlsberg has been criticised for breaking their own code of conduct for alcohol advertisement in Malawi.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=1316&artikel=2819773|title=Kaliber 3 May 2009: \"They are making us starve\"|date=2009-05-07|work=Sveriges Radio|access-date=2018-07-18|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, \"That calls for a Carlsberg\" was introduced as the new Carlsberg tagline and has appeared in various television adverts since.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.thejournal.ie/all-change-for-carlsbergs-famous-slogan-115863-Apr2011/|title= All change for Carlsberg's famous slogan|date=|work=Journal.ie|accessdate=5 April 2013 }}</ref>\nThe new-look marketing campaign was rolled out across 140 markets and included a new 30-second TV ad called 'Spaceman'. The company wants to boost sales in Asia and the Far East, but there were fears that 'probably' was too subtle as a tagline.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.joe.ie/news-politics/world-affairs/carlsberg-drop-probably-and-announce-new-slogan-and-ad-campaign-0011175-1|title= Carlsberg drop probably and announce new slogan and ad campaign|date=|work=Joe.ie|accessdate=5 April 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1373913/Carlsberg-doesnt-slogans--Lager-firm-probably-going-drop-famous-catchline.html|title= Carlsberg doesn't do slogans... Lager firm is probably going to drop famous catchline|date=6 April 2011|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=5 April 2013|location=London}}</ref>\n\n=== Sponsorships ===\nSponsorships from Carlsberg comes in two forms, sharply separated: either from the Carlsberg Brewery as part of their commercial campaigns, or as significant contributions to arts and sciences via the [[Carlsberg Foundation]] (who owns the brewery).\n\nCarlsberg Brewery was one of the major sponsors of [[Euro 2008]],<ref name=\"Euro\">{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/investor/news/Pages/carlsbergtosponsoreuro2004and2008-HQ2002.aspx | title=Carlsberg to sponsor EURO2004 and 2008 | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> [[UEFA Euro 2012 sponsorship|Euro 2012]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/media/PressKits/Pages/CarlsbergofficialsponsorofEURO2012.aspx | title=EURO 2012 sponsorship | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> and also [[UEFA Euro 2016]] (where their adboards were changed to read their abridged tagline, \"Probably\", due to [[Loi Evin|France's laws against alcohol advertising]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/mediaservices/mediareleases/newsid=1945036.html|title=Carlsberg signs as Official Sponsor for UEFA national team competitions|last=UEFA|publisher=UEFA.com|accessdate=12 Jun 2016}}</ref> Carlsberg was one of the major [[sponsor (commercial)|sponsor]]s of the [[2004 European Football Championship]]<ref name=\"Euro\" /> and use the promotional slogan \"probably the best lager in the world\";<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.adslogans.co.uk/site/pages/gallery/probably-the-best-lager-in-the-world.8375.php | title=Advertising Slogan Hall of Fame | publisher=AdSlogans | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> they were also a sponsor of the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/media/PressKits/Documents/Carlsberg%20involved%20in%20football%20for%2030%20years.pdf | title=Carlsberg involved in football for 30 years | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> Carlsberg are best known in the UK as the main and shirt sponsors of [[Liverpool F.C.]] having sponsored the club from 1992 continuing through to 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/investor/news/Pages/liverpool21.aspx#.Vm8CzuIj6nk | title=Liverpool Football Club and Carlsberg Toast 21 Year Partnership | publisher=Carslberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> With Liverpool being the only UK city exhibiting at the [[World Expo in Shanghai]] \u2013 its twin city, the Carlsberg logo on the Liverpool F.C jersey was written in Chinese for the league match against [[Chelsea F.C]] on 2 May 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.soccerbible.com/performance/football-apparel/2010/05/liverpool-fc-shirt-chinese-sponsor-carlsberg/ | title=Liverpool FC Home Shirt 2009/10 - Carlsberg Chinese Edition | publisher=SoccerBible Ltd. | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:J\u00f8rgen Buhl Rasmussen and Peter Schmeichel 2012-01-03 001.jpg|thumb|Carlsberg CEO [[J\u00f8rgen Buhl Rasmussen]]\n (left) and brand ambassador [[Peter Schmeichel]] (right)]]\nCarlsberg also sponsor [[F.C. Copenhagen]], [[Havant and Waterlooville]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://havantandwaterlooville.co.uk/newsprint.asp?item=951 | title=Carlsberg to continue sponsorship deal | publisher=havantandwaterlooville.net | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> [[Odense Boldklub]],<ref name=\"Sponsor\">{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/media/PressKits/Documents/Carlsberg%20and%20Football%20factsheet.pdf | title=Fact Sheet Background on Carlsberg and Football | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> [[PFC Pirin Blagoevgrad|Pirin Blagoevgrad]] and are also the secondary sponsor (after [[Eircom]]) of the [[Republic of Ireland national football team]]<ref name=\"Sponsor\"/> and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.]].<ref name=\"Sponsor\"/> Carlsberg also sponsors other sport events, such as [[golf]] and [[skiing]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.premiumbeer.ca/ourbrands/carlsberg.html | title=The Premium Beer Company | publisher=Premium Beer Company | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> On 13 July 2011 Carlsberg signed a sponsorship contract with [[Hajduk Split]] and contributed 40,000 Euros to the team to help avert a financial crisis in 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.croatiaweek.com/hajduk-split-fans-drinking-earns-club-e40k-cheque-from-carlsberg/ | title=Hajduk Split Fans Drinking Earns Club \u20ac40k Cheque From Carlsberg | publisher=Croatia Week | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> \n\nAs of August 2011 Carlsberg also became [[Arsenal F.C]]'s official beer sponsor for three years.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/media/IntheMedia/Pages/CarlsbergandArsenalFootballClub.aspx | title=Carlsberg becomes Official Beer Partner of Arsenal Football Club | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> Carlsberg has also sponsored the Hong Kong Rugby Sevens in 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/uth-creative-secures-carlsberg-rugby-sevens-work/ | title=Uth Creative secures Carlsberg's Rugby Sevens work | publisher=Marketing-Interactive.com. Lighthouse Independent Media Pte Ltd. | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> Carlsberg was also the sponsor of the [[Indian Premier League]] (IPL) franchise [[Kings XI Punjab]] in season 4 of the league, with its logo appearing on the caps and helmets of the team.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bestmediainfo.com/2011/04/ipl-4-kings-xi-punjab-kick-starts-its-marketing-campaign/ | title=IPL 4: Kings XI Punjab kick starts its Marketing campaign | publisher=BestMediaInfo.com | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nGoalkeeper [[Peter Schmeichel]] is the first ever World Wide ambassador for Carlsberg. He will be the face of Carlsberg\u2019s ambitious UEFA Euro 2016 sponsorship campaign.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thedrum.com/news/2015/12/11/peter-schmeichel-front-carlsbergs-euro-2016-sponsorship-campaign | title=Peter Schmeichel to front Carlsberg's Euro 2016 sponsorship campaign | publisher=Carnyx Group Ltd | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Niels Bohr Institute|The Institute of Theoretical Physics]] (also known as the \"Niels Bohr Institute\") in [[Copenhagen]], which was one of the leading international centers for theoretical physics during the 1920s and 1930s and is said to be the birthplace of [[quantum mechanics]], was created in 1921 with significant funding from the [[Carlsberg Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexknapp/2012/11/28/for-winning-the-nobel-prize-niels-bohr-got-a-house-with-free-beer/ | title=For Winning The Nobel Prize, Niels Bohr Got A House With Free Beer | publisher=Forbes Tech | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> Other projects funded by the Carlsberg Foundation include: Dating the Greenland Ice Core, Uncovering the Iron-Age in Northern Europe, \nDiscovering the Secrets of Molecular Diversity, and Creating Dictionaries on the Web.<ref name=\"The Carlsberg Foundation\"/>\n\n== Controversy ==\nA factory in Nepal owned by Carlsberg has been shown to severely pollute a nearby river.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/penge/knuste-flasker-og-forurening-belaster-carlsbergs-nye-bryggeri-i-nepal |title=Knuste flasker og forurening belaster Carlsbergs nye bryggeri i Nepal |date=March 8, 2018 |access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> Initially Carlsberg denied the pollution, but has since admitted the wrongdoing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/penge/carlsberg-tager-ansvar-forurening-ved-bryggeri-i-nepal}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portalbar|Companies|Beer|Denmark}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Carlsberg Group}}\n\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.carlsberg.com Carlsberg Beer website]\n\n{{Danish beer}}\n{{OMX Copenhagen 20 companies}}\n\n[[Category:Carlsberg Group| ]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Copenhagen Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Breweries in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies based in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Multinational breweries]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1847]]\n[[Category:Danish companies established in 1847]]\n[[Category:Purveyors to the Court of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Danish brands]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Danish brewery group}}\n{{distinguish|Karlsberg (brewery)}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2015}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name  =  Carlsberg A/S\n| logo  = Carlsberg Group logo.svg\n| type  = [[Aktieselskab]]\n| traded_as  = {{OMX|CSE1595|CARL A}}, {{OMXb|CSE1596|CARL B}}\n| area_served        = Worldwide\n| founder = [[J. C. Jacobsen]]\n| key_people  = [[Cees 't Hart]] <small>(President and [[chief executive officer|CEO]])</small>, [[Flemming Besenbacher]] <small>([[Chairman]])</small>\n| industry  = [[Beverages]]\n| products  = [[Beer]]s, [[cider]]s, [[soft drink]]s, [[bottled water]]\n| brands  =  Carlsberg, [[Tuborg]], [[Kronenbourg 1664]], [[Baltika]], [[Grimbergen (beer)|Grimbergen]], [[Somersby cider|Somersby]]\n| revenue  = [[Danish krone|DKK]] 62.6 billion ($9.48 billion) <small>(2016)</small><ref name=\"AR2016\">{{cite web |url=https://carlsberggroup.com/media/10899/carlsberg-group-annual-report-2016.pdf |title=Annual Report 2016}}</ref>\n| profit  =  DKK 8.2 billion ($1.24 billion) <small>(2016)</small><ref name=\"AR2016\" />\n| num_employees  = 41,000 <small>([[full-time equivalent|FTE]], average 2016)</small><ref name=\"AR2016\" />\n| homepage  =  [http://www.carlsberggroup.com/ www.carlsberggroup.com]\n| foundation  =  {{Start date and age|1847}}\n| location  =   [[Copenhagen]], Denmark\n}}\n'''Carlsberg A/S''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|k|\u0251\u02d0r|l|z|b|\u025c\u02d0r|\u0261}}; {{IPA-da|\u02c8k\u02b0\u0251\u02c0ls\u02ccp\u025b\u0250\u032f\u02c0|lang}}) is a Danish multinational brewer. Founded in 1847 by [[J. C. Jacobsen]], the company's headquarters is located in [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]]. Since Jacobsen's death in 1887, the majority owner of the company has been the [[Carlsberg Foundation]]. The company's flagship brand is [[#Carlsberg|Carlsberg]] (named after Jacobsen's son [[Carl Jacobsen|Carl]]). It also brews [[Tuborg]], [[Kronenbourg]], [[Somersby cider]], Russia's best-selling beer [[Baltika]], Belgian [[Grimbergen (beer)|Grimbergen]] abbey beers, and more than 500 local beers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/brands/Pages/Default.aspx |title=Carlsberg \u2013 Brands home<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=19 March 2008 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120207204742/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/brands/Pages/Default.aspx |archive-date=7 February 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nThe company employs around 41,000 people, primarily located in Western Europe, Eastern Europe and Asia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carlsberggroup.com/media/10899/carlsberg-group-annual-report-2016.pdf|title=Carlsberg Group Annual Report 2016}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Image:J C Jacobsen.jpg|thumb|J.C. Jacobsen standing in his winter garden known as ''[[Carlsberg (district)#Carlsberg Academy|Pompeji]]'', next to a table with laboratory equipment, a bottle of lager, a beer glass, and books by [[Louis Pasteur]] and [[Emil Christian Hansen]]. Painting by [[August Jerndorff]] (1886)]] \n[[Image:EXPO 1885 Carlsberg.jpg|thumb|Diplome d'Honneur Antwerp 1885 expo]]\nCarlsberg was founded by [[J. C. Jacobsen]], a [[philanthropist]] and avid art collector. With his fortune he amassed an art collection which is housed in the [[Ny Carlsberg Glyptotek]] in central Copenhagen. The first brew was finished on 10 November 1847, and the export of Carlsberg beer began in 1868 with the export of one barrel to [[Edinburgh]], [[Scotland]].<ref name=\"Carl\">{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberguk.co.uk/AboutUs/heritage/Pages/Global.aspx | title=Carlsberg Group - Our Heritage | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015 }}{{Dead link|date=October 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Some of the company's original logos include an elephant, after which some of its lagers are named, and the [[swastika]], the use of which was discontinued in the 1930s because of its association with political parties in neighboring Germany.\n\nJacobsen's son Carl opened a brewery in 1882 named Ny (New) Carlsberg forcing him to rename his brewery Gamle (Old) Carlsberg. The companies were merged and run under Carl's direction in 1906 and remained so until his death in 1914.<ref name=\"Carl\"/>\n\nJacobsen set up the [[Carlsberg Laboratory]] in 1875, which worked on scientific problems related to brewing. It featured a Department of Chemistry and a Department of Physiology. The species of yeast used to make [[pale lager]], ''[[Saccharomyces carlsbergensis]]'', was isolated by Emil Christian Hansen at the laboratory in 1883 and bears its name; this was shared freely by Carlsberg.<ref name=\"Carl\"/> The Carlsberg Laboratory also developed the concept of [[pH]] and made advances in protein chemistry.<ref name=euchems>{{cite web|url=http://www.euchems.org/Distinguished/20thCentury/sorensen.asp|title=S\u00f8rensen, S\u00f8ren Peter Lauritz (1868\u20131939)|accessdate=9 January 2007|work=100 Distinguished European Chemists|publisher=European Association for Chemical and Molecular Sciences|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20061004013146/http://www.euchems.org/Distinguished/20thCentury/sorensen.asp|archive-date=4 October 2006|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 1972, the Carlsberg Research Centre was established and the Carlsberg Laboratory is an independent unit of the Centre.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsbergfondet.dk/en/Afdelinger/Carlsberg%20Laboratorium.aspx | title=The Carlssberg Laboratory | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 1876, J.C. Jacobsen established the Carlsberg Foundation, run by trustees from the Royal Danish Academy of Sciences and Letters,  which managed the Carlsberg Laboratory as well as supporting scientific research within the fields of natural sciences, mathematics, philosophy, the humanities and social sciences in Denmark. Because of a conflict with his son Carl, Jacobsen's brewery was left to the Foundation upon his death in 1887.<ref name=\"The Carlsberg Foundation\">{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Company/Foundations/CARLSBERGFOUNDATION/Pages/Default.aspx | title=The Carlsberg Foundation | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe first overseas license for brewing was given to the Photos Photiades Breweries, and in 1966 Carlsberg beer was brewed for the first time outside Denmark at the Photiades breweries in Cyprus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://carlsberggroup.com/who-we-are/about-the-carlsberg-group/our-rich-heritage/|title=Who we are \" About the Carlsberg Group \" Our Rich Heritage \" Carlsberg Group|website=Carlsberg Group|language=en|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref> The first brewery to be built outside Denmark was in [[Blantyre|Blantyre, Malawi]] in 1968.<ref name=\"Carl\"/>\n\nCarlsberg merged with Tuborg breweries in 1970 forming the United Breweries AS, and merged with [[Tetley's (beer)|Tetley]] in 1992. Carlsberg became the sole owner of Carlsberg-Tetley in 1997.<ref name=\"Carl\"/>\n\nIn 2008 Carlsberg Group, together with [[Heineken International|Heineken]], bought [[Scottish & Newcastle]], the largest brewer in the UK, for \u00a37.8bn ($15.3bn).<ref name=BBCJan2508>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/business/7208341.stm |title=Brewer S&N agrees \u00a37.8bn takeover |author= |date=25 January 2008 |publisher=BBC }}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 the company joined leading alcohol producers as part of a [[International Alliance for Responsible Drinking|producers' commitments]] to reducing harmful drinking.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Home {{!}} Producers' Commitments|url = http://www.producerscommitments.org/|website = Producers' Commitments|accessdate = 2015-12-23|language = en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, Carlsberg agreed to take over [[Greece]]'s third largest brewery, the [[Olympic Brewery]], adding to its operations in the country already and effectively transforming the firm into the second biggest market player in Greece.<ref>{{cite press release | publisher=Reuters| date=18 November 2014| title=Carlsberg becomes no.2 in Greece with Olympic Brewery takeover | url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/18/us-carlsberg-greece-idUSKCN0J20KY20141118}}</ref>\n\nThe old brewery in Copenhagen is open for tours.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.visitcarlsberg.com/#the-flow | title=Visit Carlsberg | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> In January 2020 The Brewery Tour is closed for a complete refurbishment. it is not known when it will reopen <ref>C</ref>Carlsberg website\n\n== Regional operations ==\nThe Carlsberg Group divides their operations into three market areas: Northern and Western Europe, Eastern Europe and Asia.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.carlsberggroup.com/investor/companyprofile/Pages/default.aspx |title=Carlsberg Group - Company Profile  |work=carlsberggroup.com |year=2012 |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n=== Eastern Europe ===\n[[Baltic Beverages Holding]] is owned by Carlsberg. Previously, it was a joint venture between Carlsberg and [[Scottish & Newcastle]] in Russia.<ref name=BBCJan2508/> The company is a significant operator in the brewing industry in Russia, [[Ukraine]], the [[Baltic countries]], [[Kazakhstan]] and [[Uzbekistan]]. It has a majority interest in [[Baltika Breweries|OAO Baltika Breweries]], the largest brewery in the [[Russian Federation]] and [[Eastern Europe]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/ee/Pages/Russia.aspx |title=Russia - Baltika Breweries |publisher=Carlsberg Group }}</ref>\n\nThe Uzbek government claimed the subsidiary owed $4.6 million in taxes from unreported revenue. Lower courts also claimed that Carlsberg illegally produced 1.6 million litres of beer from 2008 to 2010. For these reasons, in March 2012, Carlsberg suspended production at its Uzbek plant and asked its employees to take an unpaid leave.<ref>{{cite news|title=Uzbek Court Rules Against Carlsberg Subsidiary|url=http://www.satrapia.com/news/article/uzbek-court-rules-against-carlsberg-subsidiary/|newspaper=The Gazette of Central Asia|date=20 October 2012|publisher=Satrapia}}</ref> In late 2012, the Uzbek Court declined Carlsberg's tax appeal.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://enews.fergananews.com/news.php?id=2389&mode=snews | title=Uzbekistan: Court declined tax appeal by Carlsberg Uzbekistan | publisher=Ferghana News Agency | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> Production resumed in April 2013.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.themoscowtimes.com/news/article/uzbekistan-central-asias-poisoned-chalice/483598.html | title=Uzbekistan, Central Asia's Poisoned Chalice | newspaper=Moscow Times | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> The brewery produces 1.3 million litres of beer under three local brands Sarbast Original, Sarbast Extra, and Sarbast Special, plus the international brand Tuborg Green.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/ee/Pages/Uzbekistan.aspx | title=Carslberg Group - Uzbekistan | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Northern and Western Europe ===\nCarlsberg acquired the [[Aldaris Brewery]] in Riga, [[Latvia]], in 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/NWE/Pages/Latvia.aspx |title=Carlsberg Group - Latvia |work=carlsberggroup.com |year=2012 |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> The brewery was founded in 1865, and produces Aldaris brand beers.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ratebeer.com/brewers//aldaris-carlsberg/852/ |title=Aldaris (Carlsberg) - RateBeer |work=ratebeer.com |year=2012 |quote=Aldaris |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n\n[[Carlsberg Polska]] is the Polish subsidiary of the Carlsberg Group. Carlsberg acquired 100% control of the Okocim Group, which included the [[Okocim Brewery]], in 2004. The [[subsidiary]] owns four [[brewing plant]]s and employs a staff of 1,250. It is the third largest brewing company in [[Poland]] with a 14.4% [[market share]].<ref>[http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Company/Markets/Pages/Poland.aspx Carlsberg \u2013 Poland] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327113235/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Company/Markets/Pages/Poland.aspx |date=27 March 2010 }}</ref> Brands include Harna\u015b, [[Carlsberg Polska#Kasztelan Brewery|Kasztelan]], [[Okocim Brewery|Okocim]], [[Piast Brewery|Piast]], Somersby and Carlsberg.\n\nCarlsberg Sweden (Sverige) is based in [[Stockholm]], and owns the [[Falcon Brewery]] in [[Falkenberg]], and the [[Raml\u00f6sa]] mineral water bottling facility in [[Helsingborg]].<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/NWE/Pages/Sweden.aspx |title=Carlsberg Group - Sweden |work=carlsberggroup.com |year=2012 |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref> Carnegie Porter, a 5.5% abv [[Baltic porter]], along with the [[Pripps]] and Falcon brand lagers, are brewed in Falkenberg.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.ratebeer.com/brewer/765/sort/0/ |title=Carlsberg Sverige - RateBeer |work=ratebeer.com |year=2012 |accessdate=3 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nNorway brands include: Arendals, [[E. C. Dahls Brewery|Dahls]], [[Frydenlund]], Nordlands, [[Ringnes]] and [[Tou (brewery)|Tou]].\n\nOther European brands include: [[Birrificio Angelo Poretti]] (Italy), [[Feldschl\u00f6sschen]] (Switzerland), [[Holsten]] (Germany), [[Jacobsen (beer)|Jacobsen]], [[Karhu (beer)|Karhu]] (Finland), [[Kronenbourg]] (France), [[Super Bock]] (Portugal) and [[Tetley's (beer)|Tetley]] (UK).\nA result of the take over of [[Scottish & Newcastle]], Carlsberg controls the [[San Miguel Corporation|San Miguel]] brand in the UK.\n\n===North America===\nIn the US, the Carlsberg group brands are distributed by St. Killian Import Co., based in Everett, Massachusetts, importing Carlsberg beer directly from Denmark. Brands that are imported include: Carlsberg Beer (bottles and kegs), Carlsberg Elephant, Kronenbourg 1664, Grimbergen, Tetley's English Ale, Okocim.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Carlsberg Group - USA|url = http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/ExLid/Pages/USA.aspx|website = www.carlsberggroup.com|accessdate = 2015-11-16}}</ref>\n\nCarlsberg was brewed in Canada by [[Canadian Breweries]]/[[Carling O'Keefe]] beginning in 1972.<ref>https://justbeerapp.com/brand/carlsberg-group-1</ref> After Carling O'Keefe was merged with Molsons, Carlsberg opened its own brewery. Since 2008, Carlsberg no longer brews Carlsberg in Canada, instead, it imports Carlsberg along with its other brands.\n\n=== Asia ===\n====East Asia====\nCarlsberg started to export beer to [[China]] in 1876.<ref name=CarlsberginChina/> In the late 1990s, Carlsberg had two breweries in China \u2013 [[Huizhou]] and [[Shanghai]]. The company acquired Huizhou Brewery in [[Guangdong]] Province in 1995, which started to supply both the mainland Chinese and [[Hong Kong]] market.<ref name=CarlsberginChina>{{cite journal|title=Carlsberg in China |url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/investor/downloadcentre/Documents/Other%20Presentations/27.11.06%20Carlsberg%20in%20China%20.pdf |date=27 November 2006 |publisher=Carlsberg }}</ref> Carlsberg invested around US$30 million in its Shanghai brewery, and started production in 1998. In 2000, Carlsberg sold a majority stake in its Shanghai brewery to [[Tsingtao Brewery]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Carlsberg sells majority stake in Chinese brewery |url=http://www.brandrepublic.com/news/11369/Carlsberg-sells-majority-stake-Chinese-brewery/ |date=10 August 2000 |author=Camilla Palmer |publisher=Brand Republic }}</ref> Carlsberg formerly had a brewery in [[Tai Po]], Hong Kong, which was established in 1981, but shut it down in 1999<ref name=CarlsbergChina/> due to high costs.\n\nIn 2003, Carlsberg acquired the Kunming Brewery and the Dali Brewery in [[Yunnan]] province. At the time, the Dali Brewery was the largest beer brewery in Yunnan.<ref>{{cite web|title=Carlsberg Asia acquired second brewery in the Yunnan province, China |url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/investor/news/Pages/carlsbergasiaacquiressecondbreweryintheyunnanprov-HQ2003.aspx |date=6 October 2003 |publisher=Carlsberg }}</ref> In 2004, Carlsberg became a major shareholder in Lhasa Brewery in the [[Tibet Autonomous Region]]. At 3,700 metres above sea level, Lhasa Brewery is believed to be the highest altitude brewery in the Carlsberg Group.<ref name=CarlsbergChina>{{cite web|url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/asia/Pages/China.aspx |title=Carlsberg China}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Carlsberg sold its remaining interest in the Shanghai brewery to Tsingtao Brewery.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chinadaily.com.cn/business/2008-09/11/content_7017885.htm |title=Tsingtao snaps up brewery |date=11 September 2008 |author=Zhou Yan |newspaper=China Daily }}</ref>\n\nIn August 2011, Carlsberg announced a new joint venture with Chongqing Brewery and Chongqing Light Textile Holding. Chongqing Light Textile Holding is a major shareholder of Chongqing Brewery. The joint venture, to be called Chongqing Xinghui Investment Co., Ltd, would operate twelve breweries in China in [[Chongqing]], [[Sichuan]], [[Guangxi]], [[Guizhou]] and [[Hunan]]. Chongqing Brewery would contribute five breweries and Chongqing Light Textile Holding would contribute seven breweries to the joint venture. Carlsberg would inject 160 million [[Danish crowns]] (about US$30.90 million) and have a 30% interest in the venture.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2011/08/01/carlsberg-china-venture-idUSLDE77013320110801 |title=Carlsberg says to own 30 pct of new China venture |date=1 August 2011 |author=John Acher |work=Reuters }}</ref>\n\nCarlsberg also owns Wusu Beer Group in [[Urumqi]], [[Xinjiang]] in Northwest China.\n\n====South Asia====\nCarlsberg India Pvt. Ltd. headquartered in Gurgaon, India is a foreign direct investment company formed to brew and market Carlsberg beer in India. The company has also brought the Tuborg and Palone brands to India. Palone is sold as a 'strong' beer with 7.5% alcohol by volume. Strong beers dominate the Indian market, estimated in 2008 to total approximately 17 million hectolitres with over a 72% share. Carlsberg is available in most states of India, with five operational breweries in: Alwar (Rajasthan), Aurangabad (Maharashtra) both of which started in the summer of 2008, the former Hacke-Beck brewery in Paonta Sahib (Himachal Pradesh) where brewing commenced in July 2007, Kolkata (West Bengal) opened in September 2009, Patna Brewery (Patna) opened for brewing in 2014, Dharuhera Brewery opened on 7 May 2013, and Hyderabad (Telangana) opened in December 2010. Carlsberg India Pvt. Ltd. currently employs over 700 people and is headed by Michael Norgaard Jensen, Managing Director.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsbergindia.com/company/MD_message/Pages/MD'sMessage.aspx | title=Managing Director's Message | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Southeast Asia====\nCarlsberg Brewery Malaysia Berhad (Carlsberg Malaysia) was incorporated in December 1969, and began brewing Carlsberg Green Label locally in 1972. It is located in [[Petaling Jaya]], [[Selangor]]. Since then, the brand has become one of the leading beer brands with more than a 50% share of the Malaysian market. It manufactures and distribute beer, stout and other beverages mainly in the domestic market and has investments in Sri Lanka, Singapore and in a Malaysian alcoholic beverage company. Brands under Carlsberg Malaysia include: Carlsberg Green Label, Carlsberg Smooth Draught, Carlsberg Special Brew, Kronenbourg 1664 Blanc, Asahi Super Dry, Somersby Apple Cider, SKOL beer, Danish Royal Stout, Corona Extra, Jolly Shandy Lemon and as well as non-alcoholic Nutrimalt drink. In addition, Carlsberg Malaysia through its subsidiaries, has a wide range of imported international beer brands including Hoegaarden, Stella Artois, Budweiser, Grimbergen and Beck\u2019s. However CBMB sold off their subsidiaries and focus to grow Carlsberg Group brand.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsbergmalaysia.com.my/web/company/cm_carlsbergmsia.aspx | title=Carlsberg Malaysia | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2013, Carlsberg announced the formation of a joint venture with the Myanmar Golden Star (MGS) group to establish a beer production facility in the Bago Industrial Zone, about an hour's drive from [[Yangon]], [[Myanmar]]. Carlsberg will hold a majority 51 per cent stake in the venture and will provide seed capital in the range of $35 million to $50 million, with construction slated to commence in February.<ref name=burmanew>\n{{Cite news\n| title = Carlsberg takes a sip in Myanmar\n| publisher = Investvine.com\n| date = 1 February 2013\n| url= http://investvine.com/carlsberg-takes-a-sip-in-myanmar/\n| accessdate =14 February 2013}}\n</ref>\n\n[[Singha]] beer began being produced by Carlsberg's Russian plant for distribution in European markets in March 2013.<ref name=ref2013021407>\n    {{Cite news\n    | title = Singha starts roll-out in Asia and Europe\n    | publisher = Investvine.com\n    | date = 14 February 2013\n    | url= http://investvine.com/singha-starts-roll-out-in-asia-and-europe/\n    | accessdate =3 April 2013}}\n</ref> \n\nOther Southeast Asian brands include Halida Beer (Vietnam).\n\n====West Asia====\nIn [[Israel]], the [[Israel Beer Breweries]] in [[Ashkelon]] produces Carlsberg and [[Tuborg Brewery|Tuborg]]. Carlsberg and Tuborg were launched on the Israeli market in 1992. Initially they were imported from Copenhagen, but in 1995 local production began at a greenfield brewery. The brewery is situated above a large underground aquifer<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/ExLid/Pages/Israel.aspx |title=Archived copy |access-date=30 March 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130125111124/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Markets/ExLid/Pages/Israel.aspx |archive-date=25 January 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n== Beers ==\n\n=== Carlsberg{{anchor|Carlsberg Beer|Carlsberg Lager|Carlsberg Pilsner}} ===\n\n[[Image:33 cl Carlsberg beer bottle.png|thumb|100px|upright|A 33cl Carlsberg profile bottle]]\n\nCarlsberg is the flagship beer brand in Carlsberg Group's portfolio of 155 brands. It is a 5% abv [[pilsner]] beer (3.8% in the UK and branded as Carlsberg Danish Pilsener) with a global distribution to 140 markets.<ref>{{cite web\n| url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/brands/Pages/carlsberg.aspx\n| title=Carlsberg beer product information\n| publisher=www.carlsberggroup.com\n| accessdate=4 March 2014\n| last=\n| first=\n}}</ref> \nIt is also known as Carlsberg Lager, Carlsberg Beer and Carlsberg Pilsner. It was first brewed in 1904,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/brands/Pages/CarlsbergPilsner.aspx |title=Carlsberg Group \u2013 Carlsberg Pilsner |publisher=www.carlsberggroup.com |accessdate=21 October 2009 }}</ref> and was created by [[Carl Jacobsen]], son of Carlsberg's founder [[JC Jacobsen]].\n\nThe introduction of the Carlsberg pilsner also saw the reintroduction of the [[Art Nouveau]]-style logo that has been used nearly unmodified since 1904, and later became the logo of the entire company. It was designed by [[Thorvald Bindesb\u00f8ll]].<ref name=\"Carl\"/>\n\nIn Denmark the beer is often known as ''Hof'' ([[Noble court|court]]) due to its [[Royal warrant of appointment|Royal Warrant]]. This nickname was adopted into the brand in 1931 but discontinued in Denmark in 1991. The term is still used in other markets such as the UK and Sweden.<ref>[http://www.carlsbergsverige.se/Drycker/ol/Sidor/CarlsbergHof.aspx Carlsbergsverige.se - Carlsberg Hof]</ref>\n\n=== Special Brew ===\n{{Redirect|Special Brew|the ska song of the same name|Special Brew (song)}}<!-- Redirect is to this specific subsection -->\n\nSpecial Brew is a [[strong lager]] brewed only in Denmark and the United Kingdom. It was initially brewed by Carlsberg to commemorate a visit to Denmark by [[Winston Churchill]] in 1950.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/brands/Pages/Carlsbergspecialbrew.aspx |title=Carlsberg Group \u2013 Carlsberg Special Brew |publisher=www.carlsberggroup.com |accessdate=7 March 2011}}</ref> The flavour incorporates \"cognac flavours among its tasting notes\" as Churchill was partial to brandy. In May 1951 two crates were delivered to Churchill's London home. In a thank-you letter Churchill called the drink \"Commemoration Lager\". In Denmark the drink was called {{lang|da|P\u00e5skebryg}}&nbsp;(\"Easter Brew\"), but the Easter Brew has since been replaced by a weaker beer ({{lang|da|Carls P\u00e5ske}}). For the British market Carlsberg called the drink Special Brew, and production was started in [[Northampton]] in the 1950s.\n\nAt 7.5% alcohol (previously 9%, then 8% for a short time), Special Brew is part of a group of strong lagers that are termed \"super-strength\" in the UK and [[malt liquor]] in the USA. This beer is often associated with street alcoholics.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2005/oct/03/drugsandalcohol.homelessness | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Matthew | last=Weaver | title=Call for ban on super-strength 'tramp juice' | date=3 October 2005}}</ref>\n\nA single can (440mL) of Special Brew contains 3.5 [[Unit of alcohol|units of alcohol]] (previously 4.5 units) whilst the maximum recommended daily intake for a man is two units. In January 2015, it was reported that Carlsberg would reduce the units per can to less than four, in line with a UK government pledge that no single can should contain more than four units. The change, a reduction either in the size of the can from 500mL to 440mL, or the alcoholic strength of the beer, was considered for implementation in 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/blogs-magazine-monitor-30795336 |title=The secret history of Special Brew |publisher=BBC |accessdate=13 January 2015}}</ref> Both changes were made; the cans have since been reduced to 440 mL, and the ABV reduced from 9% to 8%, then another drop to 7.5%.\n\n=== Elephant beer ===\n[[Image:Elefantporten (Carlsberg).jpg|thumb|200px|The [[Elephant Gate and Tower, Carlsberg|Elephant Gate]] in Copenhagen, Denmark]] \n[[Image:Carlsberg Elephant Beer.jpg|thumb|upright|50px|Elephant beer]]\nIn 1901, at brewer Carl Jacobsen's initiative, the Architect Professor J. L. Dahlerup created a tower resting on four elephants carved in granite from the Danish island of [[Bornholm]]. Jacobsen's inspiration was the obelisk supporting an elephant on the [[Piazza della Minerva]] in Rome.<ref>[http://www.visitcarlsberg.dk/history/Footprints/Valby/Pages/TheElephantTower.aspx Visit Carlsberg]</ref> The four elephants each bear the initial of one of Carl Jacobsen's children: Theodora, Paula, Helge and Vagn. This became known as The Elephant Gate and is a landmark entrance to the brewery.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} \n\nTo the west of the gate, Carl Jacobsen's motto was inscribed: Laboremus pro Patria (Let us work for our country). Since then, the Elephant has been a famous part of the Carlsberg family, especially after the strong Elephant Beer was created in 1955 under the name Export Lager Beer featuring the Elephant label. The Elephant is still brewed in Carlsberg Breweries in Copenhagen and exported around the world. A few markets brew their own Carlsberg Elephant beer locally according to the original recipe.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Other brands in Carlsberg Group's portfolio===\n{{div col}}\n* [[Tuborg]] (International)\n* [[Somersby cider]]s (International)\n* [[Kronenbourg]] / 1664 (International)\n* [[Grimbergen (beer)|Grimbergen]] (International)\n* [[Holsten Brewery|Holsten]] (International)\n* [[Baltika]] (Russia)\n* [[Carlsberg Polska#Bosman Brewery|Bosman]]  (Poland)\n* [[Dali Beer]] (China) \n* [[Feldschl\u00f6sschen]] ([[Switzerland]])\n* [[Gorkha Beer]]  ([[Nepal]])\n* [[Jacobsen (beer)|Jacobsen]] ([[Nordic countries]])\n* [[Lav pivo|Lav]] ([[Serbia]])\n* [[Lao Brewery Company|Beerlao]] ([[Laos]])\n* [[Lvivske]] ([[Ukraine]])\n* [[Mythos Brewery|Mythos]] ([[Greece]])\n* [[Fix (beer)|FIX Hellas]] ([[Greece]])\n* [[Pan (beer)|Pan]] ([[Croatia]])\n* [[Pirinsko]] ([[Bulgaria]])\n* Ringnes (Norway)\n* [[Saku (beer)|Saku]] ([[Estonia]])\n* Sarbast ([[Uzbekistan]])\n* [[Semper Ardens]] ([[Denmark]])\n* [[Shumensko]] ([[Bulgaria]])\n* [[Slavutych Brewery|Slavutych]] ([[Ukraine]])\n* [[Super Bock]] ([[Portugal]])\n* [[\u0160vyturys]] ([[Lithuania]])\n* [[Wusu]] (China)\n* Wiibroe (Denmark)\n{{div col end}}\n[[Image:Carlsberg beers.jpg|thumb|Carlsberg beers]]\nIn total, Carlsberg Group brews more than 500 different beers.\n[https://web.archive.org/web/20120207204742/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/brands/Pages/Default.aspx A selection of brands brewed by breweries owned by Carlsberg Group.]\n\n== Visitors Centre ==\nThe Carlsberg Visitors Centre is located at 11 Gamle Carlsberg Vej, 2500 [[Valby]], [[Denmark]] at the location of the first Carlsberg Brewery. In the courtyard is a smaller replica of the [[The Little Mermaid (statue)|Little Mermaid Statue]] that [[Carl Jacobsen]] donated to [[Copenhagen]]. Also located in connection with the Carlsberg visitors Centre is the Jacobsen House Brewery, a micro brewery creating the Jacobsen speciality range of hand-crafted beers.<ref>[http://www.jacobsenbryg.dk/home/index.htm][http://www.visitcarlsberg.dk/Pages/default.aspx] dead links</ref>\nThe entry ticket includes a free drink at the bar. Visit Carlsberg is located a five-minute walk from the Carlsberg train station.<ref>[http://www.visitcopenhagen.com/content/tourist/what_to_see_and_do/inspiration/top_10_alternative/carlsberg_brewery Carlsberg Brewery www.visitcopenhagen.com]</ref>\n\n== Advertising ==\n[[File:2013 Woodstock 111 Carlsberg.jpg|thumb|Carlsberg advertising at [[Woodstock Festival (Poland)]].]]\nCarlsberg's tagline \"Probably the best lager in the world\" was created in 1973 by Tony Bodinetz at KMP for the UK market.<ref>{{LinkedIn URL | https://www.linkedin.com/in/tony-bodinetz-99408381 | Tony Bodinetz}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Foster |first1=Stephen |title=Carlsberg enlists Belgian bikers in great beer battle |url=https://www.moreaboutadvertising.com/2011/10/carlsberg-enlists-belgian-bikers-in-great-beer-battle/ |website=More About Advertising |accessdate=22 August 2018}}</ref> It began to appear in company corporate ads around the world from the 1980s onwards until it was replaced in 2011 in most regions by new tagline \"That calls for a Carlsberg\".<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/jorgen-rasmussen-right-time-for-change-of-tactics-probably-6273789.html|title= Jorgen Rasmussen: Right time for change of tactics? Probably...|date=8 December 2011|work=The Independent|accessdate=5 April 2013|location=London|first=James|last=Thompson}}</ref>\nThe voice over for the original ad in 1983 was voiced by actor [[Orson Welles]],<ref>http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Company/Timeline/Pages/History.aspx  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080213062037/http://www.carlsberggroup.com/Company/Timeline/Pages/History.aspx |date=13 February 2008 }}</ref> his voice has been used repeatedly over the years. Welles was not expensive and he liked the advertisements, so he kept his fees to a minimum. In some countries the tagline has been adapted to \"Probably the best beer in the world\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Stamp|first=Gavin|title=Probably the best corporate slogan...|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/5036084.stm|accessdate=17 January 2015|work=BBC News|date=18 June 2006}}</ref>\n\nCarlsberg was featured in the film ''[[Ice Cold in Alex]]'' (not, however, in the book on which the film was based) as the lager the main cast get to drink after driving across the desert. Lines from the film gave rise to one of Carlsberg's best known advertising slogans in the UK: \"worth waiting for\".\n\nCarlsberg has been criticised for breaking their own code of conduct for alcohol advertisement in Malawi.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://sverigesradio.se/sida/artikel.aspx?programid=1316&artikel=2819773|title=Kaliber 3 May 2009: \"They are making us starve\"|date=2009-05-07|work=Sveriges Radio|access-date=2018-07-18|language=sv}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, \"That calls for a Carlsberg\" was introduced as the new Carlsberg tagline and has appeared in various television adverts since.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.thejournal.ie/all-change-for-carlsbergs-famous-slogan-115863-Apr2011/|title= All change for Carlsberg's famous slogan|date=|work=Journal.ie|accessdate=5 April 2013 }}</ref>\nThe new-look marketing campaign was rolled out across 140 markets and included a new 30-second TV ad called 'Spaceman'. The company wants to boost sales in Asia and the Far East, but there were fears that 'probably' was too subtle as a tagline.<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.joe.ie/news-politics/world-affairs/carlsberg-drop-probably-and-announce-new-slogan-and-ad-campaign-0011175-1|title= Carlsberg drop probably and announce new slogan and ad campaign|date=|work=Joe.ie|accessdate=5 April 2013 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url= http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-1373913/Carlsberg-doesnt-slogans--Lager-firm-probably-going-drop-famous-catchline.html|title= Carlsberg doesn't do slogans... Lager firm is probably going to drop famous catchline|date=6 April 2011|work=Daily Mail|accessdate=5 April 2013|location=London}}</ref>\n\n=== Sponsorships ===\nSponsorships from Carlsberg comes in two forms, sharply separated: either from the Carlsberg Brewery as part of their commercial campaigns, or as significant contributions to arts and sciences via the [[Carlsberg Foundation]] (who owns the brewery).\n\nCarlsberg Brewery was one of the major sponsors of [[Euro 2008]],<ref name=\"Euro\">{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/investor/news/Pages/carlsbergtosponsoreuro2004and2008-HQ2002.aspx | title=Carlsberg to sponsor EURO2004 and 2008 | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> [[UEFA Euro 2012 sponsorship|Euro 2012]]<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/media/PressKits/Pages/CarlsbergofficialsponsorofEURO2012.aspx | title=EURO 2012 sponsorship | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> and also [[UEFA Euro 2016]] (where their adboards were changed to read their abridged tagline, \"Probably\", due to [[Loi Evin|France's laws against alcohol advertising]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefa/mediaservices/mediareleases/newsid=1945036.html|title=Carlsberg signs as Official Sponsor for UEFA national team competitions|last=UEFA|publisher=UEFA.com|accessdate=12 Jun 2016}}</ref> Carlsberg was one of the major [[sponsor (commercial)|sponsor]]s of the [[2004 European Football Championship]]<ref name=\"Euro\" /> and use the promotional slogan \"probably the best lager in the world\";<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.adslogans.co.uk/site/pages/gallery/probably-the-best-lager-in-the-world.8375.php | title=Advertising Slogan Hall of Fame | publisher=AdSlogans | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> they were also a sponsor of the [[1990 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/media/PressKits/Documents/Carlsberg%20involved%20in%20football%20for%2030%20years.pdf | title=Carlsberg involved in football for 30 years | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> Carlsberg are best known in the UK as the main and shirt sponsors of [[Liverpool F.C.]] having sponsored the club from 1992 continuing through to 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/investor/news/Pages/liverpool21.aspx#.Vm8CzuIj6nk | title=Liverpool Football Club and Carlsberg Toast 21 Year Partnership | publisher=Carslberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> With Liverpool being the only UK city exhibiting at the [[World Expo in Shanghai]] \u2013 its twin city, the Carlsberg logo on the Liverpool F.C jersey was written in Chinese for the league match against [[Chelsea F.C]] on 2 May 2010.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.soccerbible.com/performance/football-apparel/2010/05/liverpool-fc-shirt-chinese-sponsor-carlsberg/ | title=Liverpool FC Home Shirt 2009/10 - Carlsberg Chinese Edition | publisher=SoccerBible Ltd. | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:J\u00f8rgen Buhl Rasmussen and Peter Schmeichel 2012-01-03 001.jpg|thumb|Carlsberg CEO [[J\u00f8rgen Buhl Rasmussen]]\n (left) and brand ambassador [[Peter Schmeichel]] (right)]]\nCarlsberg also sponsor [[F.C. Copenhagen]], [[Havant and Waterlooville]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://havantandwaterlooville.co.uk/newsprint.asp?item=951 | title=Carlsberg to continue sponsorship deal | publisher=havantandwaterlooville.net | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> [[Odense Boldklub]],<ref name=\"Sponsor\">{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/media/PressKits/Documents/Carlsberg%20and%20Football%20factsheet.pdf | title=Fact Sheet Background on Carlsberg and Football | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> [[PFC Pirin Blagoevgrad|Pirin Blagoevgrad]] and are also the secondary sponsor (after [[Eircom]]) of the [[Republic of Ireland national football team]]<ref name=\"Sponsor\"/> and [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.]].<ref name=\"Sponsor\"/> Carlsberg also sponsors other sport events, such as [[golf]] and [[skiing]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.premiumbeer.ca/ourbrands/carlsberg.html | title=The Premium Beer Company | publisher=Premium Beer Company | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> On 13 July 2011 Carlsberg signed a sponsorship contract with [[Hajduk Split]] and contributed 40,000 Euros to the team to help avert a financial crisis in 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.croatiaweek.com/hajduk-split-fans-drinking-earns-club-e40k-cheque-from-carlsberg/ | title=Hajduk Split Fans Drinking Earns Club \u20ac40k Cheque From Carlsberg | publisher=Croatia Week | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> \n\nAs of August 2011 Carlsberg also became [[Arsenal F.C]]'s official beer sponsor for three years.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.carlsberggroup.com/media/IntheMedia/Pages/CarlsbergandArsenalFootballClub.aspx | title=Carlsberg becomes Official Beer Partner of Arsenal Football Club | publisher=Carlsberg | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> Carlsberg has also sponsored the Hong Kong Rugby Sevens in 2015.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.marketing-interactive.com/uth-creative-secures-carlsberg-rugby-sevens-work/ | title=Uth Creative secures Carlsberg's Rugby Sevens work | publisher=Marketing-Interactive.com. Lighthouse Independent Media Pte Ltd. | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> Carlsberg was also the sponsor of the [[Indian Premier League]] (IPL) franchise [[Kings XI Punjab]] in season 4 of the league, with its logo appearing on the caps and helmets of the team.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.bestmediainfo.com/2011/04/ipl-4-kings-xi-punjab-kick-starts-its-marketing-campaign/ | title=IPL 4: Kings XI Punjab kick starts its Marketing campaign | publisher=BestMediaInfo.com | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nGoalkeeper [[Peter Schmeichel]] is the first ever World Wide ambassador for Carlsberg. He will be the face of Carlsberg\u2019s ambitious UEFA Euro 2016 sponsorship campaign.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thedrum.com/news/2015/12/11/peter-schmeichel-front-carlsbergs-euro-2016-sponsorship-campaign | title=Peter Schmeichel to front Carlsberg's Euro 2016 sponsorship campaign | publisher=Carnyx Group Ltd | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[Niels Bohr Institute|The Institute of Theoretical Physics]] (also known as the \"Niels Bohr Institute\") in [[Copenhagen]], which was one of the leading international centers for theoretical physics during the 1920s and 1930s and is said to be the birthplace of [[quantum mechanics]], was created in 1921 with significant funding from the [[Carlsberg Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/alexknapp/2012/11/28/for-winning-the-nobel-prize-niels-bohr-got-a-house-with-free-beer/ | title=For Winning The Nobel Prize, Niels Bohr Got A House With Free Beer | publisher=Forbes Tech | accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> Other projects funded by the Carlsberg Foundation include: Dating the Greenland Ice Core, Uncovering the Iron-Age in Northern Europe, \nDiscovering the Secrets of Molecular Diversity, and Creating Dictionaries on the Web.<ref name=\"The Carlsberg Foundation\"/>\n\n== Controversy ==\nA factory in Nepal owned by Carlsberg has been shown to severely pollute a nearby river.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/penge/knuste-flasker-og-forurening-belaster-carlsbergs-nye-bryggeri-i-nepal |title=Knuste flasker og forurening belaster Carlsbergs nye bryggeri i Nepal |date=March 8, 2018 |access-date=March 8, 2018}}</ref> Initially Carlsberg denied the pollution, but has since admitted the wrongdoing.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dr.dk/nyheder/penge/carlsberg-tager-ansvar-forurening-ved-bryggeri-i-nepal}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portalbar|Companies|Beer|Denmark}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Carlsberg Group}}\n\n* {{Official website}}\n* [http://www.carlsberg.com Carlsberg Beer website]\n\n{{Danish beer}}\n{{OMX Copenhagen 20 companies}}\n\n[[Category:Carlsberg Group| ]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on the Copenhagen Stock Exchange]]\n[[Category:Breweries in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies based in Copenhagen]]\n[[Category:Multinational breweries]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in Denmark]]\n[[Category:Food and drink companies established in 1847]]\n[[Category:Danish companies established in 1847]]\n[[Category:Purveyors to the Court of Denmark]]\n[[Category:Danish brands]]\n", "name_user": "103.246.36.93", "label": "vandal", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eElephant beer)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carlsberg_Group"}
{"title_page": "Haplogroup DE", "text_new": "{{Infobox haplogroup\n| name         = DE\n| map          = \n| origin-date  = 70,000-75,000 or already 141,000 years split between [[Haplogroup CF (Y-DNA)|CF]] and DE,<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1038/nature12736|pmid=24256729|pmc=4105016|title=Upper Palaeolithic Siberian genome reveals dual ancestry of Native Americans|journal=Nature|volume=505|issue=7481|pages=87\u201391|year=2014|last1=Raghavan|first1=Maanasa|last2=Skoglund|first2=Pontus|last3=Graf|first3=Kelly E.|last4=Metspalu|first4=Mait|last5=Albrechtsen|first5=Anders|last6=Moltke|first6=Ida|last7=Rasmussen|first7=Simon|last8=Stafford Jr|first8=Thomas W.|last9=Orlando|first9=Ludovic|last10=Metspalu|first10=Ene|last11=Karmin|first11=Monika|last12=Tambets|first12=Kristiina|last13=Rootsi|first13=Siiri|last14=M\u00e4gi|first14=Reedik|last15=Campos|first15=Paula F.|last16=Balanovska|first16=Elena|last17=Balanovsky|first17=Oleg|last18=Khusnutdinova|first18=Elza|last19=Litvinov|first19=Sergey|last20=Osipova|first20=Ludmila P.|last21=Fedorova|first21=Sardana A.|last22=Voevoda|first22=Mikhail I.|last23=Degiorgio|first23=Michael|last24=Sicheritz-Ponten|first24=Thomas|last25=Brunak|first25=S\u00f8ren|last26=Demeshchenko|first26=Svetlana|last27=Kivisild|first27=Toomas|last28=Villems|first28=Richard|last29=Nielsen|first29=Rasmus|last30=Jakobsson|first30=Mattias|last31=Willerslev|first31=Eske|bibcode=2014Natur.505...87R}}</ref> ca. 73,100 years ago,<ref name=\"A recent bottleneck of Y chromosome\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kamin M, Saag L, Vincente M, et al. | title = A recent bottleneck of Y chromosome diversity coincides with a global change in culture\n | journal = Genome Research | volume = 25\n | issue = 4\n | pages = 459\u2013466\n | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25770088 | pmc = 4381518\n | doi = 10.1101/gr.186684.114 }}</ref> or ca. 76,000 years ago<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Haber M, Jones AL, Connel BA, Asan, Arciero E, Huanming Y, Thomas MG, Xue Y, Tyler-Smith C | title = A Rare Deep-Rooting D0 African Y-chromosomal Haplogroup and its Implications for the Expansion of Modern Humans Out of Africa | journal = Genetics | pages = genetics.302368.2019 | date = June 2019 | pmid = 31196864 | doi = 10.1534/genetics.119.302368 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n| origin-place = [[Africa]]<ref name=\"underhill2007\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/><ref>{{cite bioRxiv|vauthors=Cabrera VM|title=Carriers of mitochondrial DNA macrohaplogroup L3 basic lineages migrated back to Africa from Asia around 70,000 years ago|date=2017|biorxiv=10.1101/233502}}</ref>\n| ancestor     = [[Haplogroup CT (Y-DNA)|CT]]\n| descendants  = [[Haplogroup E (Y-DNA)|E]], [[Haplogroup D (Y-DNA)|D]]\n| mutations    = M1/YAP, M145 = P205, M203, P144, P153, P165, P167, P183\n| members      =\n}}\n\n'''Haplogroup DE''' is a [[human Y-chromosome DNA haplogroup]]. It is defined by the [[single nucleotide polymorphism]] (SNP) mutations, or UEPs, M1(YAP), M145(P205), M203, P144, P153, P165, P167, P183.<ref>[http://www.isogg.org/tree/ISOGG_YDNATreeTrunk08.html ISOGG reference webpage.]</ref> DE is unique because it is distributed in several geographically distinct clusters. An immediate subclade, haplogroup [[Haplogroup D (Y-DNA)|D]] (also known as D-CTS3946), is mainly found in Eastern [[Asia]], parts of Central Asia, and the [[Andaman Islands]], but also sporadically in [[West Africa]] and [[West Asia]]. The other immediate subclade, haplogroup [[Haplogroup E (Y-DNA)|E]], is common in [[Africa]], and to a lesser extent the [[Middle East]] and [[Europe]].\n\nThe most well-known [[unique event polymorphism]] (UEP) that defines DE is the '''Y-chromosome Alu [[Polymorphism (biology)|Polymorphism]]''' \"YAP''\"''. The mutation was caused when a strand of DNA, known as [[Alu sequence|Alu]], inserted a copy of itself into the [[Y chromosome]]. Hence, all Y chromosomes belonging to DE, D, E and their subclades are YAP-positive (YAP+). All Y chromosomes that belong to other haplogroups and subclades are YAP-negative (YAP-).\n\nThe age of haplogroup DE, previously estimated at between 65,000 and 71,000 years,<ref name=Karafet>{{cite journal | vauthors = Karafet TM, Mendez FL, Meilerman MB, Underhill PA, Zegura SL, Hammer MF | title = New binary polymorphisms reshape and increase resolution of the human Y chromosomal haplogroup tree | journal = Genome Research | volume = 18 | issue = 5 | pages = 830\u20138 | date = May 2008 | pmid = 18385274 | pmc = 2336805 | doi = 10.1101/gr.7172008 }}</ref> was later estimated at around 73,000 years <ref name=\"A recent bottleneck of Y chromosome\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kamin M, Saag L, Vincente M, et al. | title = A recent bottleneck of Y chromosome diversity coincides with a global change in culture\n | journal = Genome Research | volume = 25\n | issue = 4\n | pages = 459\u2013466\n | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25770088 | pmc = 4381518\n | doi = 10.1101/gr.186684.114 }}</ref> and most recently at around 76,000 years old.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\" />\n\n==Distribution==\nThe subclades of DE continue to confound investigators trying to reconstruct the migration of humans because, while they are common in Africa and East Asia, they are also largely absent between these two regions. As the [[paragroup]] DE(xD,E), including DE*, is extremely rare, the majority of DE male lines fall into subclades of either [[Haplogroup D (Y-DNA)|D-CTS3946]] or [[Haplogroup E (Y-DNA)|E-M96]]. D-CTS3946 is suggested to have originated in Africa,<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> though its most widespread subclade, [[Haplogroup D (Y-DNA)|D-M174]], likely originated in [[Asia]] \u2013 the only place where D-M174 is now found.<ref name=\"Karafet\"/> E-M96 is more likely to have originated in [[East Africa]].<ref name=\"underhill\">{{cite book|title=Genetic, Linguistic and Archaeological Perspectives on Human Diversity in Southeast Asia|last=Underhill|year=2001|isbn=981-02-4784-2|chapter=The case for an African rather than an Asian origin of the human Y-chromosome YAP insertion|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tzKLqyx315sC&printsec=frontcover#PPA43,M1|publisher=World Scientific|location=New Jersey}}</ref><ref name=Cruciani2004>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cruciani F, La Fratta R, Santolamazza P, Sellitto D, Pascone R, Moral P, Watson E, Guida V, Colomb EB, Zaharova B, Lavinha J, Vona G, Aman R, Cali F, Akar N, Richards M, Torroni A, Novelletto A, Scozzari R | title = Phylogeographic analysis of haplogroup E3b (E-M215) y chromosomes reveals multiple migratory events within and out of Africa | journal = American Journal of Human Genetics | volume = 74 | issue = 5 | pages = 1014\u201322 | date = May 2004 | pmid = 15042509 | pmc = 1181964 | doi = 10.1086/386294 }}</ref> However, a [[West Asia]]n origin for E-M96 is considered possible by some scholars.<ref name=\"Chandrasekar2007\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Chandrasekar A, Saheb SY, Gangopadyaya P, Gangopadyaya S, Mukherjee A, Basu D, Lakshmi GR, Sahani AK, Das B, Battacharya S, Kumar S, Xaviour D, Sun D, Rao VR | title = YAP insertion signature in South Asia | journal = Annals of Human Biology | volume = 34 | issue = 5 | pages = 582\u20136 | year = 2007 | pmid = 17786594 | doi = 10.1080/03014460701556262 }}</ref> \nAll subclades of DE, including D and E, appear to be exceptionally rare \u2013 almost non-existent \u2013 in mainland South Asia and South East Asia. Given that D-M174 is dominant in Japan, the Andaman Islands, and Tibet, whereas E-M96 is relatively common in Africa and the Middle East, some researchers have suggested that the rarity of DE lineages in India \u2013 a region considered important in the dispersal of modern humans \u2013 may be meaningful.<ref name=\"underhill2007\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Underhill PA, Kivisild T|year=2007|title=Use of y chromosome and mitochondrial DNA population structure in tracing human migrations|journal=Annual Review of Genetics|volume=41|issue=|pages=539\u201364|doi=10.1146/annurev.genet.41.110306.130407|pmid=18076332}}</ref> By comparison, subclades of [[haplogroup CF|CF]] \u2013 the only \"sibling\" haplogroup of DE \u2013 are found in India at significant proportions. \n    \n'''DE*'''<br/>[[Basal (phylogenetics)|Basal]] DE* is extremely unusual in that it is found, at very low frequencies, among males from three widely separated regions: [[West Africa]], the [[Caribbean]], and [[Asia]].\n\nA 2003 study by Weale et al., of the DNA of over 8,000 males worldwide, found that five out of 1,247 [[Nigeria]]n males belonged to DE*. The DE* found possessed by these five Nigerians, according to the study's authors, was \"the least derived of all YAP chromosomes according to currently known binary markers\" \u2013 to such an extent that it suggested that DE had originated in West Africa and expanded from there. However, Weale et al., cautioned that such inferences may well be incorrect. In addition, the seemingly \"[[paraphyletic]]\" (basal) status of the Nigerian examples of DE-YAP may be \"illusory\" because the \"branching order, and hence the origin, of YAP-derived haplogroups remains uncertain\". It was \"easy to misinterpret apparently paraphyletic groups\", and subsequent research might show that the Nigerian examples of DE were as divergent from DE*, D* and E*. \"[T]he only genealogically meaningful definition of the age of a clade is the time to its most recent common ancestor, but only if DE* is [truly] paraphyletic does it ... become automatically older than D or E...\" The relationship between DE*, according to Weale et al., \"can be viewed as a missing-data problem...\"<ref name=\"weale\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Weale ME, Shah T, Jones AL, Greenhalgh J, Wilson JF, Nymadawa P, Zeitlin D, Connell BA, Bradman N, Thomas MG | title = Rare deep-rooting Y chromosome lineages in humans: lessons for phylogeography | journal = Genetics | volume = 165 | issue = 1 | pages = 229\u201334 | date = September 2003 | pmid = 14504230 | pmc = 1462739 | url = http://www.genetics.org/cgi/content/full/165/1/229 }}</ref> In 2007, another West African example of DE* was reported \u2013 carried by a speaker of the [[Nalu language]] who was among 17 Y-DNA samples taken in [[Guinea Bissau]]. The sequence of this individual differed by one mutation from those of the Nigerian individuals, indicating common ancestry, although the relationship between the two lineages has not been determined.<ref name=\"rosa2007\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rosa A, Ornelas C, Jobling MA, Brehm A, Villems R | title = Y-chromosomal diversity in the population of Guinea-Bissau: a multiethnic perspective | journal = BMC Evolutionary Biology | volume = 7 | issue =  | pages = 124 | date = July 2007 | pmid = 17662131 | pmc = 1976131 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2148-7-124 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, members of a tribal group in [[Karnataka]], [[India]] were found to belong to DE, at a frequency of about 0.6% of the total group tested, but were not excluded from sub-haplogroups of DE.<ref>Independent origins of Indian caste and tribal paternal lineages. - Cordaux R, et al. Curr Biol. 2004</ref> More recent studies have not found any further DE* in India.<ref>A comprehensive portrait of Y-STR diversity of Indian populations and comparison with 129 worldwide populations. - Singh M et al. Nature. 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 2008, a basal paternal marker belonging to DE* was identified in two individuals from [[Tibet]] (two out of 594), belonging to the [[Tibeto-Burman languages|Tibeto-Burman group]].<ref name=\"shi\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Shi H, Zhong H, Peng Y, Dong YL, Qi XB, Zhang F, Liu LF, Tan SJ, Ma RZ, Xiao CJ, Wells RS, Jin L, Su B | title = Y chromosome evidence of earliest modern human settlement in East Asia and multiple origins of Tibetan and Japanese populations | journal = BMC Biology | volume = 6 | issue =  | pages = 45 | date = October 2008 | pmid = 18959782 | pmc = 2605740 | doi = 10.1186/1741-7007-6-45  }}</ref>\n\nA 2010 study found six additional samples of DE in southeastern Nigeria in individuals of the [[Ibibio people|Ibibio]], [[Igbo people|Igbo]], and [[Oron people|Oron]] ethnic groups.<ref name=\"Veeramah\">{{Cite journal|title=Little genetic differentiation as assessed by uniparental markers in the presence of substantial language variation in peoples of the Cross River region of Nigeria|journal=BMC Evolutionary Biology|year=2010|pages=1\u201317|doi=10.1186/1471-2148-10-92| pmid=20356404 |vauthors=Veeramah RK, , Connell AB, Pour AN, Powell A, Plaster AC, Zeitlyn D, Mendell RN, Weale EM, Bradman N, Thomas GM|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, haplogroup DE* was found in one Caribbean sample.<ref name=\"Simms\">{{Cite journal|title=Y-chromosomal diversity in Haiti and Jamaica: Contrasting levels of sex-biased gene flow|journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology|year=2012|pages=618\u201331|doi=10.1002/ajpa.22090| pmid=22576450 |vauthors=Simms TM, Wright MR, Hernandez M, Perez OA, Ramirez EC, Martinez E, Herrera RJ}}</ref>\n\nA 2019 study by Haber et al. suggested that three of the Nigerians analysed by Weale et al. in 2003 belonged, not to DE*, but to D0, a proposed haplogroup thought to represent a deep-rooting DE lineage branching close to the DE bifurcation (near the split of D and E) but on the D branch as an outgroup to all other known D chromosomes.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> Another carrier of D0 (the D-FT75 branch) is famous [[figure skating|skater]]<ref>https://tass.ru/moskva/7434455</ref> [[Ruslan bin Makin Al-Bitar]] from [[Syria]].<ref>https://www.familytreedna.com/public/sidoroff/default.aspx?section=yresults</ref> Recently two other D0 samples were found in [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=\"Estes\">{{Cite web|url=https://dna-explained.com/2019/06/21/exciting-new-y-dna-haplogroup-d-discoveries/|title=Exciting New Y DNA Haplogroup D Discoveries!|last=Estes|first=Roberta|date=2019-06-21|website=DNAeXplained - Genetic Genealogy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n\nIn the Recent ISOGG tree, D0 was renamed D2, and D-M174 was renamed D1.\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:Y-DNA tree.GIF|thumb|right|upright=1.25|Most parsimonious phylogeny of YAP according to Underhill and Kivisild 2007<ref name=\"underhill2007\"/>]]\n\n===Discovery===\nThe YAP insertion was discovered by scientists led by Michael Hammer of the University of Arizona.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hammer MF | title = A recent insertion of an alu element on the Y chromosome is a useful marker for human population studies | journal = Molecular Biology and Evolution | volume = 11 | issue = 5 | pages = 749\u201361 | date = September 1994 | pmid = 7968488 | doi = 10.1093/oxfordjournals.molbev.a040155 | doi-access = free }}</ref> Between 1997 and 1998 Hammer published three articles relating to the origins of haplogroup DE.<ref name=\"hammer1997\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hammer MF, Karafet T, Rasanayagam A, Wood ET, Altheide TK, Jenkins T, Griffiths RC, Templeton AR, Zegura SL | title = Out of Africa and back again: nested cladistic analysis of human Y chromosome variation | journal = Molecular Biology and Evolution | volume = 15 | issue = 4 | pages = 427\u201341 | date = April 1998 | pmid = 9549093 | doi = 10.1093/oxfordjournals.molbev.a025939 | doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name=\"altheide1997\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Altheide TK, Hammer MF | title = Evidence for a possible Asian origin of YAP+ Y chromosomes | journal = American Journal of Human Genetics | volume = 61 | issue = 2 | pages = 462\u20136 | date = August 1997 | pmid = 9311756 | pmc = 1715891 | doi = 10.1016/S0002-9297(07)64077-4 }}</ref><ref name=\"hammer1998\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hammer MF, Spurdle AB, Karafet T, Bonner MR, Wood ET, Novelletto A, Malaspina P, Mitchell RJ, Horai S, Jenkins T, Zegura SL | title = The geographic distribution of human Y chromosome variation | journal = Genetics | volume = 145 | issue = 3 | pages = 787\u2013805 | date = March 1997 | pmid = 9055088 | pmc = 1207863 | url = http://www.genetics.org/cgi/reprint/145/3/787 }}</ref> These articles state that YAP insertion originated in Asia. As recently as 2007, some studies such as Chandrasekar et al. 2007, cite the publications by Hammer when arguing for an Asian origin of the YAP insertion.<ref name=\"Chandrasekar2007\"/>\n\nThe scenarios outlined by Hammer include an out of Africa migration over 100,000 years ago, the YAP+ insertion on an Asian Y-chromosome 55,000 years ago and a back migration of YAP+ from Asia to Africa 31,000 years ago by its subclade haplogroup E.<ref name=\"hammer1998\"/> This analysis was based on the fact that older African lineages, such as [[Haplogroup A (Y-DNA)|haplogroups A]] and [[Haplogroup B (Y-DNA)|B]], were YAP negative whereas the younger lineage, [[Haplogroup E (Y-DNA)|haplogroup E]] was YAP positive. Haplogroup D, which is YAP positive, was clearly an Asian lineage, being found only in East Asia with high frequencies in the Andaman Islands, Japan and Tibet. Because the mutations that define haplogroup E were observed to be in the ancestral state in haplogroup D, and haplogroup D at 55kya, was considerably older than haplogroup E at 31kya, Hammer concluded that haplogroup E was a subclade of haplogroup D and migrated back to Africa.<ref name=\"hammer1998\"/>\n\nA 2000 study concerning the origin of the YAP+ mutation analyzed 841 Y-chromosomes representing 36 human populations of wide geographical distribution for the presence of a Y-specific Alu insert (YAP+ chromosomes). They also analyzed the Out-of-Africa and out-of-Asia models for the YAP mutations. According to the authors, the most ancient YAP+ mutation was found in the Asian lineage of Tibetans, but curiously not in Japanese lineages. More recent YAP+ lineages were distributed almost equally in Asians and Africans, with a smaller distribution in Europe. The scientists concluded that the information available did not allow one to decide between the out-of-Asia or out-of-Africa models. They further suggested that the YAP+ mutation had already originated 141,000 years ago.<ref>Origin of YAP+ lineages of the human Y\u2010chromosome - M. Bravi et al.{{full citation needed|date=July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Contemporary studies===\n\nSince 2000, a number of scientists began to reassess the hypothesis of an Asian origin of the YAP insertion and to suggest an African origin.<ref name=\"underhill\" />\n\nUnderhill et al. 2001 identified the D-M174 mutation that defines [[haplogroup D (Y-DNA)|haplogroup D]]. The M174 allele is found in the ancestral state in all African lineages including haplogroup E. The discovery of M174 mutation meant that haplogroup E could not be a subclade of haplogroup D. These findings effectively neutralized the argument of an Asian origin of the YAP+ based on the character state of the M40 and M96 mutations that define haplogroup E. According to Underhill et al. 2001, the M174 data alone would support an African origin of the YAP insertion.<ref name=\"underhill2000\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Underhill PA, Passarino G, Lin AA, Shen P, Miraz\u00f3n Lahr M, Foley RA, Oefner PJ, Cavalli-Sforza LL | title = The phylogeography of Y chromosome binary haplotypes and the origins of modern human populations | journal = Annals of Human Genetics | volume = 65 | issue = Pt 1 | pages = 43\u201362 | date = January 2001 | pmid = 11415522 | doi = 10.1046/j.1469-1809.2001.6510043.x | url = http://www.human-evol.cam.ac.uk/Members/Lahr/pubs/AHG-65-01.pdf | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090815134944/http://www.human-evol.cam.ac.uk/Members/Lahr/pubs/AHG-65-01.pdf | df =  | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2009-08-15 }}</ref>\n\nIn Altheide and Hammer 1997, the authors argue that haplogroup E arose in Asia on an ancestral YAP+ allele before migrating back to Africa.<ref name=\"altheide1997\"/> However some studies, such as Semino et al., indicate that the highest frequency and diversity of haplogroup E is in Africa, and East Africa is the most likely place of origin of the haplogroup.<ref name=\"semino\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Semino O, Magri C, Benuzzi G, Lin AA, Al-Zahery N, Battaglia V, Maccioni L, Triantaphyllidis C, Shen P, Oefner PJ, Zhivotovsky LA, King R, Torroni A, Cavalli-Sforza LL, Underhill PA, Santachiara-Benerecetti AS | title = Origin, diffusion, and differentiation of Y-chromosome haplogroups E and J: inferences on the neolithization of Europe and later migratory events in the Mediterranean area | journal = American Journal of Human Genetics | volume = 74 | issue = 5 | pages = 1023\u201334 | date = May 2004 | pmid = 15069642 | pmc = 1181965 | doi = 10.1086/386295 }}</ref>\n\nThe models supporting an African origin or an Asian origin of the YAP+ insertion both required the extinction of the ancestral YAP chromosome to explain the current distribution of the YAP+ polymorphism. Paragroup DE* possesses neither the mutations that define haplogroup D or haplogroup E. If paragroup DE* was found in one location but not the other, it would boost one theory over the other.<ref name=\"wells\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wells RS, Yuldasheva N, Ruzibakiev R, Underhill PA, Evseeva I, Blue-Smith J, Jin L, Su B, Pitchappan R, Shanmugalakshmi S, Balakrishnan K, Read M, Pearson NM, Zerjal T, Webster MT, Zholoshvili I, Jamarjashvili E, Gambarov S, Nikbin B, Dostiev A, Aknazarov O, Zalloua P, Tsoy I, Kitaev M, Mirrakhimov M, Chariev A, Bodmer WF | title = The Eurasian heartland: a continental perspective on Y-chromosome diversity | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 98 | issue = 18 | pages = 10244\u20139 | date = August 2001 | pmid = 11526236 | pmc = 56946 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.171305098 }}</ref> Haplogroup DE* has been found in [[Nigeria]],<ref name=weale/> [[Guinea-Bissau]]<ref name=\"rosa2007\"/> and also in [[Tibet]].<ref name=\"shi\" /> The phylogenetic relationship of three DE* sequences has yet to be determined, but it is known that the Guinea Bissau sequences differ from the Nigerian sequences by at least one mutation.<ref name=\"rosa2007\"/> Weale et al. state that the discovery of DE* among Nigerians pushes back the date for the [[most recent common ancestor]] (MRCA) of African YAP chromosomes. This, in his view, has the effect of reducing the time window through which a possible back migration from Asia to Africa could occur.<ref name=weale/>\n\nChandrasekhar et al. 2007,<ref>YAP insertion signature in South Asia - Chandrasekar 2007 (https://www.researchgate.net/publication/6053145_YAP_insertion_signature_in_South_Asia)</ref> have argued for an Asian origin of the YAP+. They state: \"The presence of the YAP insertion in Northeast Indian tribes and Andaman Islanders with haplogroup D suggests that some of the M168 chromosomes gave rise to the YAP insertion and M174 mutation in South Asia.\"\nThey also argue that YAP+ migrated back to Africa with other Eurasian haplogroups, such as [[haplogroup R1b (Y-DNA)|Haplogroup R1b1]]* (18-23kya), which has been observed with especially high frequency among the members of some peoples in northern [[Cameroon]], and [[Haplogroup T (Y-DNA)|Haplogroup T]] (39-45 kya), which has been observed in low frequencies in Africa. Haplogroup E at 50kya is considerably older than these haplogroups and has been observed at frequencies of 80-92% in Africa.\n\nIn a 2007 study, Peter Underhill and Toomas Kivisild stated that there will always be uncertainty regarding the precise origins of DNA sequence variants such as YAP because of a lack of knowledge concerning prehistoric demographics and population movements. However Underhill and Kivisild contend that with all the available information, the African origin of the YAP+ polymorphism is more parsimonious and more plausible than the Asian origin hypothesis.<ref name=\"underhill2007\" />\n\nIn a press release concerning a study by Karafet et al. 2008, Michael Hammer revised the dates for the origin Haplogroup DE from 55,000 years ago to 65,000 years ago. For haplogroup E, Hammer revised the dates from 31,000 years ago to 50,000 years ago. Hammer is also quoted as saying \u201cThe age of haplogroup DE is about 65,000 years, just a bit younger than the other major lineage to leave Africa, which is assumed to be about 70,000 years old\u201d, in which he implies that haplogroup DE left Africa soon after haplogroup CT.<ref>[http://genome.cshlp.org/site/press/Ychromohaplogroup.xhtml Scientists reshape Y chromosome haplogroup tree gaining new insights into human ancestry]</ref>\n\nA 2018 study, based on analyzing maternal and paternal markers, their current distribution, and inferences from the DNA of the Altai Neanderthals, supports an Asian origin of paternal haplogroup DE and maternal haplogroup L3. The study suggests a back migration into Africa and a following admixture of the native Africans with immigrating peoples from Asia. It is suggested that DE originated about 70,000 years ago somewhere near [[Tibet]] and [[Central Asia]]. Additionally, the authors argue that the presence of DE* in Tibet, and that Tibet shows the greatest diversity concerning haplogroup D, supports the origin of DE* in this region. It is further argued that haplogroup E is of Asian origin and that the haploid diversity of haplogroup E supports a strong Eurasian male gene flow. The authors conclude that this supports an Asian origin and may also explain signals of small percentages of Neanderthal DNA found in northern and some western Africans.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Cabrera VM, Marrero P, Abu-Amero KK, Larruga JM|date=June 2018|title=Carriers of mitochondrial DNA macrohaplogroup L3 basal lineages migrated back to Africa from Asia around 70,000 years ago|journal=BMC Evolutionary Biology|volume=18|issue=1|pages=98|doi=10.1186/s12862-018-1211-4|pmc=6009813|pmid=29921229}}</ref>\n\nA 2019 study by Haber et al. supports an African origin for haplogroup DE*, based in part on the discovery of haplogroup D0 found in three Nigerians (according to the authors a branch of the DE lineage near the DE split but on the D branch), as well as on an analysis of y-chromosomal phylogeny, recently calculated haplogroup divergence dates and evidence for ancestral Eurasians outside Africa. The authors consider other possible scenarios, but conclude in favor of a model involving an African origin of hapologroup DE, with haplogroups E and D0 also originating in Africa, along with the migration out of Africa of the three lineages (C, D and FT) that now form the vast majority of non-African Y chromosomes. The authors find divergence times for DE*, E, and D0, all likely within a period of about 76,000-71,000 years ago, and a likely date for the exit of the ancestors of modern Eurasians out of Africa (and ensuing Neanderthal admixture) later around 50,300-59,400 years ago, which they argue, also supports an African origin for those haplogroups.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/>\n\n[[FTDNA]], in 2019, found three other D0 samples: one in Syria (the most basal sample of D0 found to date, diverging about 26,000 years ago), and two in Saudi Arabia. According to Runfeldt and Sager of FTDNA (as also found by Haber et al.), D0 is a very divergent offshoot on the D branch, diverging around 71,000 years ago, and lacking the M174 mutation that defines other D chromosomes. According to their schematics D0 can be grouped into an Asian cluster (West Asia) and African cluster (Nigeria). Two D0 branches were confirmed: D-FT75 found in West Asia and D-FT76 found in West Asia and West Africa. \"D0\" has also been alternately named \"D2\", and former D (D-M174) has now been termed \"D1\", since the discovery of D0. The research team says they will continue to analyze additional samples.<ref name=\"Estes\"/>\n\nBoth theories (Out-of-Africa and Out-of-Asia) regarding the origin of haplogroup DE are discussed and more studies are needed to conclude about a proposed origin.\n\n==Tree==\nBy ISOGG tree\uff08Version: 14.151\uff09.<ref>[https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1QBUFZl03X92qNN61lQ8VtIKwbBMeuBzvqXQ47IQPBps/edit#gid=437997455]</ref>\n\n*'''DE''' (YAP)\n**'''[[Haplogroup D (Y-DNA)|D]]''' (CTS3946)\n***'''D1''' (M174/Page30, IMS-JST021355, [[Haplogroup D-M174]])\n****'''D1a''' (CTS11577)\u3000\n*****'''[[Haplogroup D-Z27276|D1a1]]''' (F6251/Z27276)\n******'''D1a1a''' (M15)\u3000[[Tibet]]\n******'''D1a1b''' (P99)\u3000[[Tibet]], [[Mongol]], [[Central Asia]]\n*****'''[[Haplogroup D-M55|D1a2]]''' (M64.1/Page44.1, M55) \u3000 [[Japan]]\uff08[[Yamato people]]\u3001[[Ryukyuan people]]\u3001[[Ainu people]]\uff09\n*****'''D1a3''' (Y34637)\u3000[[Andaman Islands]]\uff08[[Onge people]]\u3001[[Jarawa (Andaman Islands)|Jarawa people]]\uff09\n****'''D1b''' (L1378) \u3000 [[Philippines]]<ref name = \"ISOGG2014\">[http://www.isogg.org/tree/ISOGG_HapgrpD.html Y-DNA Haplogroup D and its Subclades - 2014]</ref>\n***'''D2''' (A5580.2) \u3000[[Nigeria]], [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Syria]]\n\n{{Y-DNA}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Haplogroup D (Y-DNA)]]\n*[[Haplogroup E (Y-DNA)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Haplogroup DE of Y-DNA}}\n* Trombetta B. \"Phylogeographic Refinement and Large Scale Genotyping of Human Y Chromosome Haplogroup E Provide New Insights into the Dispersal of Early Pastoralists in the African Continent\" http://gbe.oxfordjournals.org/content/7/7/1940.long http://dienekes.blogspot.ru/2015/07/phylogeographic-refinement-of.html\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haplogroup De (Y-Dna)}}\n[[Category:Human Y-DNA haplogroups|DE]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox haplogroup\n| name         = DE\n| map          = \n| origin-date  = 70,000-75,000 or already 141,000 years split between [[Haplogroup CF (Y-DNA)|CF]] and DE,<ref>{{Cite journal|doi=10.1038/nature12736|pmid=24256729|pmc=4105016|title=Upper Palaeolithic Siberian genome reveals dual ancestry of Native Americans|journal=Nature|volume=505|issue=7481|pages=87\u201391|year=2014|last1=Raghavan|first1=Maanasa|last2=Skoglund|first2=Pontus|last3=Graf|first3=Kelly E.|last4=Metspalu|first4=Mait|last5=Albrechtsen|first5=Anders|last6=Moltke|first6=Ida|last7=Rasmussen|first7=Simon|last8=Stafford Jr|first8=Thomas W.|last9=Orlando|first9=Ludovic|last10=Metspalu|first10=Ene|last11=Karmin|first11=Monika|last12=Tambets|first12=Kristiina|last13=Rootsi|first13=Siiri|last14=M\u00e4gi|first14=Reedik|last15=Campos|first15=Paula F.|last16=Balanovska|first16=Elena|last17=Balanovsky|first17=Oleg|last18=Khusnutdinova|first18=Elza|last19=Litvinov|first19=Sergey|last20=Osipova|first20=Ludmila P.|last21=Fedorova|first21=Sardana A.|last22=Voevoda|first22=Mikhail I.|last23=Degiorgio|first23=Michael|last24=Sicheritz-Ponten|first24=Thomas|last25=Brunak|first25=S\u00f8ren|last26=Demeshchenko|first26=Svetlana|last27=Kivisild|first27=Toomas|last28=Villems|first28=Richard|last29=Nielsen|first29=Rasmus|last30=Jakobsson|first30=Mattias|last31=Willerslev|first31=Eske|bibcode=2014Natur.505...87R}}</ref> ca. 73,100 years ago,<ref name=\"A recent bottleneck of Y chromosome\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kamin M, Saag L, Vincente M, et al. | title = A recent bottleneck of Y chromosome diversity coincides with a global change in culture\n | journal = Genome Research | volume = 25\n | issue = 4\n | pages = 459\u2013466\n | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25770088 | pmc = 4381518\n | doi = 10.1101/gr.186684.114 }}</ref> or ca. 76,000 years ago<ref name=\"ReferenceC\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Haber M, Jones AL, Connel BA, Asan, Arciero E, Huanming Y, Thomas MG, Xue Y, Tyler-Smith C | title = A Rare Deep-Rooting D0 African Y-chromosomal Haplogroup and its Implications for the Expansion of Modern Humans Out of Africa | journal = Genetics | pages = genetics.302368.2019 | date = June 2019 | pmid = 31196864 | doi = 10.1534/genetics.119.302368 | doi-access = free }}</ref>\n| origin-place = [[Africa]]<ref name=\"underhill2007\"/><ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> or [[Eurasia]]<ref>{{cite bioRxiv|vauthors=Cabrera VM|title=Carriers of mitochondrial DNA macrohaplogroup L3 basic lineages migrated back to Africa from Asia around 70,000 years ago|date=2017|biorxiv=10.1101/233502}}</ref>\n| ancestor     = [[Haplogroup CT (Y-DNA)|CT]]\n| descendants  = [[Haplogroup E (Y-DNA)|E]], [[Haplogroup D (Y-DNA)|D]]\n| mutations    = M1/YAP, M145 = P205, M203, P144, P153, P165, P167, P183\n| members      =\n}}\n\n'''Haplogroup DE''' is a [[human Y-chromosome DNA haplogroup]]. It is defined by the [[single nucleotide polymorphism]] (SNP) mutations, or UEPs, M1(YAP), M145(P205), M203, P144, P153, P165, P167, P183.<ref>[http://www.isogg.org/tree/ISOGG_YDNATreeTrunk08.html ISOGG reference webpage.]</ref> DE is unique because it is distributed in several geographically distinct clusters. An immediate subclade, haplogroup [[Haplogroup D (Y-DNA)|D]] (also known as D-CTS3946), is mainly found in Eastern [[Asia]], parts of Central Asia, and the [[Andaman Islands]], but also sporadically in [[West Africa]] and [[West Asia]]. The other immediate subclade, haplogroup [[Haplogroup E (Y-DNA)|E]], is common in [[Africa]], and to a lesser extent the [[Middle East]] and [[Europe]].\n\nThe most well-known [[unique event polymorphism]] (UEP) that defines DE is the '''Y-chromosome Alu [[Polymorphism (biology)|Polymorphism]]''' \"YAP''\"''. The mutation was caused when a strand of DNA, known as [[Alu sequence|Alu]], inserted a copy of itself into the [[Y chromosome]]. Hence, all Y chromosomes belonging to DE, D, E and their subclades are YAP-positive (YAP+). All Y chromosomes that belong to other haplogroups and subclades are YAP-negative (YAP-).\n\nThe age of haplogroup DE, previously estimated at between 65,000 and 71,000 years,<ref name=Karafet>{{cite journal | vauthors = Karafet TM, Mendez FL, Meilerman MB, Underhill PA, Zegura SL, Hammer MF | title = New binary polymorphisms reshape and increase resolution of the human Y chromosomal haplogroup tree | journal = Genome Research | volume = 18 | issue = 5 | pages = 830\u20138 | date = May 2008 | pmid = 18385274 | pmc = 2336805 | doi = 10.1101/gr.7172008 }}</ref> was later estimated at around 73,000 years <ref name=\"A recent bottleneck of Y chromosome\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Kamin M, Saag L, Vincente M, et al. | title = A recent bottleneck of Y chromosome diversity coincides with a global change in culture\n | journal = Genome Research | volume = 25\n | issue = 4\n | pages = 459\u2013466\n | date = April 2015 | pmid = 25770088 | pmc = 4381518\n | doi = 10.1101/gr.186684.114 }}</ref> and most recently at around 76,000 years old.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\" />\n\n==Distribution==\nThe subclades of DE continue to confound investigators trying to reconstruct the migration of humans because, while they are common in Africa and East Asia, they are also largely absent between these two regions. As the [[paragroup]] DE(xD,E), including DE*, is extremely rare, the majority of DE male lines fall into subclades of either [[Haplogroup D (Y-DNA)|D-CTS3946]] or [[Haplogroup E (Y-DNA)|E-M96]]. D-CTS3946 is suggested to have originated in Africa,<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> though its most widespread subclade, [[Haplogroup D (Y-DNA)|D-M174]], likely originated in [[Asia]] \u2013 the only place where D-M174 is now found.<ref name=\"Karafet\"/> E-M96 is more likely to have originated in [[East Africa]].<ref name=\"underhill\">{{cite book|title=Genetic, Linguistic and Archaeological Perspectives on Human Diversity in Southeast Asia|last=Underhill|year=2001|isbn=981-02-4784-2|chapter=The case for an African rather than an Asian origin of the human Y-chromosome YAP insertion|url=https://books.google.com/?id=tzKLqyx315sC&printsec=frontcover#PPA43,M1|publisher=World Scientific|location=New Jersey}}</ref><ref name=Cruciani2004>{{cite journal | vauthors = Cruciani F, La Fratta R, Santolamazza P, Sellitto D, Pascone R, Moral P, Watson E, Guida V, Colomb EB, Zaharova B, Lavinha J, Vona G, Aman R, Cali F, Akar N, Richards M, Torroni A, Novelletto A, Scozzari R | title = Phylogeographic analysis of haplogroup E3b (E-M215) y chromosomes reveals multiple migratory events within and out of Africa | journal = American Journal of Human Genetics | volume = 74 | issue = 5 | pages = 1014\u201322 | date = May 2004 | pmid = 15042509 | pmc = 1181964 | doi = 10.1086/386294 }}</ref> However, a [[West Asia]]n origin for E-M96 is considered possible by some scholars.<ref name=\"Chandrasekar2007\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Chandrasekar A, Saheb SY, Gangopadyaya P, Gangopadyaya S, Mukherjee A, Basu D, Lakshmi GR, Sahani AK, Das B, Battacharya S, Kumar S, Xaviour D, Sun D, Rao VR | title = YAP insertion signature in South Asia | journal = Annals of Human Biology | volume = 34 | issue = 5 | pages = 582\u20136 | year = 2007 | pmid = 17786594 | doi = 10.1080/03014460701556262 }}</ref> \nAll subclades of DE, including D and E, appear to be exceptionally rare \u2013 almost non-existent \u2013 in mainland South Asia and South East Asia. Given that D-M174 is dominant in Japan, the Andaman Islands, and Tibet, whereas E-M96 is relatively common in Africa and the Middle East, some researchers have suggested that the rarity of DE lineages in India \u2013 a region considered important in the dispersal of modern humans \u2013 may be meaningful.<ref name=\"underhill2007\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Underhill PA, Kivisild T|year=2007|title=Use of y chromosome and mitochondrial DNA population structure in tracing human migrations|journal=Annual Review of Genetics|volume=41|issue=|pages=539\u201364|doi=10.1146/annurev.genet.41.110306.130407|pmid=18076332}}</ref> By comparison, subclades of [[haplogroup CF|CF]] \u2013 the only \"sibling\" haplogroup of DE \u2013 are found in India at significant proportions. \n    \n'''DE*'''<br/>[[Basal (phylogenetics)|Basal]] DE* is extremely unusual in that it is found, at very low frequencies, among males from three widely separated regions: [[West Africa]], the [[Caribbean]], and [[Asia]].\n\nA 2003 study by Weale et al., of the DNA of over 8,000 males worldwide, found that five out of 1,247 [[Nigeria]]n males belonged to DE*. The DE* found possessed by these five Nigerians, according to the study's authors, was \"the least derived of all YAP chromosomes according to currently known binary markers\" \u2013 to such an extent that it suggested that DE had originated in West Africa and expanded from there. However, Weale et al., cautioned that such inferences may well be incorrect. In addition, the seemingly \"[[paraphyletic]]\" (basal) status of the Nigerian examples of DE-YAP may be \"illusory\" because the \"branching order, and hence the origin, of YAP-derived haplogroups remains uncertain\". It was \"easy to misinterpret apparently paraphyletic groups\", and subsequent research might show that the Nigerian examples of DE were as divergent from DE*, D* and E*. \"[T]he only genealogically meaningful definition of the age of a clade is the time to its most recent common ancestor, but only if DE* is [truly] paraphyletic does it ... become automatically older than D or E...\" The relationship between DE*, according to Weale et al., \"can be viewed as a missing-data problem...\"<ref name=\"weale\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Weale ME, Shah T, Jones AL, Greenhalgh J, Wilson JF, Nymadawa P, Zeitlin D, Connell BA, Bradman N, Thomas MG | title = Rare deep-rooting Y chromosome lineages in humans: lessons for phylogeography | journal = Genetics | volume = 165 | issue = 1 | pages = 229\u201334 | date = September 2003 | pmid = 14504230 | pmc = 1462739 | url = http://www.genetics.org/cgi/content/full/165/1/229 }}</ref> In 2007, another West African example of DE* was reported \u2013 carried by a speaker of the [[Nalu language]] who was among 17 Y-DNA samples taken in [[Guinea Bissau]]. The sequence of this individual differed by one mutation from those of the Nigerian individuals, indicating common ancestry, although the relationship between the two lineages has not been determined.<ref name=\"rosa2007\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Rosa A, Ornelas C, Jobling MA, Brehm A, Villems R | title = Y-chromosomal diversity in the population of Guinea-Bissau: a multiethnic perspective | journal = BMC Evolutionary Biology | volume = 7 | issue =  | pages = 124 | date = July 2007 | pmid = 17662131 | pmc = 1976131 | doi = 10.1186/1471-2148-7-124 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, members of a tribal group in [[Karnataka]], [[India]] were found to belong to DE, at a frequency of about 0.6% of the total group tested, but were not excluded from sub-haplogroups of DE.<ref>Independent origins of Indian caste and tribal paternal lineages. - Cordaux R, et al. Curr Biol. 2004</ref> More recent studies have not found any further DE* in India.<ref>A comprehensive portrait of Y-STR diversity of Indian populations and comparison with 129 worldwide populations. - Singh M et al. Nature. 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 2008, a basal paternal marker belonging to DE* was identified in two individuals from [[Tibet]] (two out of 594), belonging to the [[Tibeto-Burman languages|Tibeto-Burman group]].<ref name=\"shi\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Shi H, Zhong H, Peng Y, Dong YL, Qi XB, Zhang F, Liu LF, Tan SJ, Ma RZ, Xiao CJ, Wells RS, Jin L, Su B | title = Y chromosome evidence of earliest modern human settlement in East Asia and multiple origins of Tibetan and Japanese populations | journal = BMC Biology | volume = 6 | issue =  | pages = 45 | date = October 2008 | pmid = 18959782 | pmc = 2605740 | doi = 10.1186/1741-7007-6-45  }}</ref>\n\nA 2010 study found six additional samples of DE in southeastern Nigeria in individuals of the [[Ibibio people|Ibibio]], [[Igbo people|Igbo]], and [[Oron people|Oron]] ethnic groups.<ref name=\"Veeramah\">{{Cite journal|title=Little genetic differentiation as assessed by uniparental markers in the presence of substantial language variation in peoples of the Cross River region of Nigeria|journal=BMC Evolutionary Biology|year=2010|pages=1\u201317|doi=10.1186/1471-2148-10-92| pmid=20356404 |vauthors=Veeramah RK, , Connell AB, Pour AN, Powell A, Plaster AC, Zeitlyn D, Mendell RN, Weale EM, Bradman N, Thomas GM|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, haplogroup DE* was found in one Caribbean sample.<ref name=\"Simms\">{{Cite journal|title=Y-chromosomal diversity in Haiti and Jamaica: Contrasting levels of sex-biased gene flow|journal=American Journal of Physical Anthropology|year=2012|pages=618\u201331|doi=10.1002/ajpa.22090| pmid=22576450 |vauthors=Simms TM, Wright MR, Hernandez M, Perez OA, Ramirez EC, Martinez E, Herrera RJ}}</ref>\n\nA 2019 study by Haber et al. suggested that three of the Nigerians analysed by Weale et al. in 2003 belonged, not to DE*, but to D0, a proposed haplogroup thought to represent a deep-rooting DE lineage branching close to the DE bifurcation (near the split of D and E) but on the D branch as an outgroup to all other known D chromosomes.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/> Another carrier of D0 (the D-FT75 branch) is famous [[figure skating|skater]]<ref>https://tass.ru/moskva/7434455</ref> [[Ruslan bin Makin Al-Bitar]] from [[Syria]].<ref>https://www.familytreedna.com/public/sidoroff/default.aspx?section=yresults</ref> Recently two other D0 samples were found in [[Saudi Arabia]].<ref name=\"Estes\">{{Cite web|url=https://dna-explained.com/2019/06/21/exciting-new-y-dna-haplogroup-d-discoveries/|title=Exciting New Y DNA Haplogroup D Discoveries!|last=Estes|first=Roberta|date=2019-06-21|website=DNAeXplained - Genetic Genealogy|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-06}}</ref>\n\nIn the Recent ISOGG tree, D0 was renamed D2, and D-M174 was renamed D1.\n\n==Origins==\n[[File:Y-DNA tree.GIF|thumb|right|upright=1.25|Most parsimonious phylogeny of YAP according to Underhill and Kivisild 2007<ref name=\"underhill2007\"/>]]\n\n===Discovery===\nThe YAP insertion was discovered by scientists led by Michael Hammer of the University of Arizona.<ref>{{cite journal | vauthors = Hammer MF | title = A recent insertion of an alu element on the Y chromosome is a useful marker for human population studies | journal = Molecular Biology and Evolution | volume = 11 | issue = 5 | pages = 749\u201361 | date = September 1994 | pmid = 7968488 | doi = 10.1093/oxfordjournals.molbev.a040155 | doi-access = free }}</ref> Between 1997 and 1998 Hammer published three articles relating to the origins of haplogroup DE.<ref name=\"hammer1997\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hammer MF, Karafet T, Rasanayagam A, Wood ET, Altheide TK, Jenkins T, Griffiths RC, Templeton AR, Zegura SL | title = Out of Africa and back again: nested cladistic analysis of human Y chromosome variation | journal = Molecular Biology and Evolution | volume = 15 | issue = 4 | pages = 427\u201341 | date = April 1998 | pmid = 9549093 | doi = 10.1093/oxfordjournals.molbev.a025939 | doi-access = free }}</ref><ref name=\"altheide1997\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Altheide TK, Hammer MF | title = Evidence for a possible Asian origin of YAP+ Y chromosomes | journal = American Journal of Human Genetics | volume = 61 | issue = 2 | pages = 462\u20136 | date = August 1997 | pmid = 9311756 | pmc = 1715891 | doi = 10.1016/S0002-9297(07)64077-4 }}</ref><ref name=\"hammer1998\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Hammer MF, Spurdle AB, Karafet T, Bonner MR, Wood ET, Novelletto A, Malaspina P, Mitchell RJ, Horai S, Jenkins T, Zegura SL | title = The geographic distribution of human Y chromosome variation | journal = Genetics | volume = 145 | issue = 3 | pages = 787\u2013805 | date = March 1997 | pmid = 9055088 | pmc = 1207863 | url = http://www.genetics.org/cgi/reprint/145/3/787 }}</ref> These articles state that YAP insertion originated in Asia. As recently as 2007, some studies such as Chandrasekar et al. 2007, cite the publications by Hammer when arguing for an Asian origin of the YAP insertion.<ref name=\"Chandrasekar2007\"/>\n\nThe scenarios outlined by Hammer include an out of Africa migration over 100,000 years ago, the YAP+ insertion on an Asian Y-chromosome 55,000 years ago and a back migration of YAP+ from Asia to Africa 31,000 years ago by its subclade haplogroup E.<ref name=\"hammer1998\"/> This analysis was based on the fact that older African lineages, such as [[Haplogroup A (Y-DNA)|haplogroups A]] and [[Haplogroup B (Y-DNA)|B]], were YAP negative whereas the younger lineage, [[Haplogroup E (Y-DNA)|haplogroup E]] was YAP positive. Haplogroup D, which is YAP positive, was clearly an Asian lineage, being found only in East Asia with high frequencies in the Andaman Islands, Japan and Tibet. Because the mutations that define haplogroup E were observed to be in the ancestral state in haplogroup D, and haplogroup D at 55kya, was considerably older than haplogroup E at 31kya, Hammer concluded that haplogroup E was a subclade of haplogroup D and migrated back to Africa.<ref name=\"hammer1998\"/>\n\nA 2000 study concerning the origin of the YAP+ mutation analyzed 841 Y-chromosomes representing 36 human populations of wide geographical distribution for the presence of a Y-specific Alu insert (YAP+ chromosomes). They also analyzed the Out-of-Africa and out-of-Asia models for the YAP mutations. According to the authors, the most ancient YAP+ mutation was found in the Asian lineage of Tibetans, but curiously not in Japanese lineages. More recent YAP+ lineages were distributed almost equally in Asians and Africans, with a smaller distribution in Europe. The scientists concluded that the information available did not allow one to decide between the out-of-Asia or out-of-Africa models. They further suggested that the YAP+ mutation had already originated 141,000 years ago.<ref>Origin of YAP+ lineages of the human Y\u2010chromosome - M. Bravi et al.{{full citation needed|date=July 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Contemporary studies===\n\nSince 2000, a number of scientists began to reassess the hypothesis of an Asian origin of the YAP insertion and to suggest an African origin.<ref name=\"underhill\" />\n\nUnderhill et al. 2001 identified the D-M174 mutation that defines [[haplogroup D (Y-DNA)|haplogroup D]]. The M174 allele is found in the ancestral state in all African lineages including haplogroup E. The discovery of M174 mutation meant that haplogroup E could not be a subclade of haplogroup D. These findings effectively neutralized the argument of an Asian origin of the YAP+ based on the character state of the M40 and M96 mutations that define haplogroup E. According to Underhill et al. 2001, the M174 data alone would support an African origin of the YAP insertion.<ref name=\"underhill2000\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Underhill PA, Passarino G, Lin AA, Shen P, Miraz\u00f3n Lahr M, Foley RA, Oefner PJ, Cavalli-Sforza LL | title = The phylogeography of Y chromosome binary haplotypes and the origins of modern human populations | journal = Annals of Human Genetics | volume = 65 | issue = Pt 1 | pages = 43\u201362 | date = January 2001 | pmid = 11415522 | doi = 10.1046/j.1469-1809.2001.6510043.x | url = http://www.human-evol.cam.ac.uk/Members/Lahr/pubs/AHG-65-01.pdf | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090815134944/http://www.human-evol.cam.ac.uk/Members/Lahr/pubs/AHG-65-01.pdf | df =  | url-status = dead | archive-date = 2009-08-15 }}</ref>\n\nIn Altheide and Hammer 1997, the authors argue that haplogroup E arose in Asia on an ancestral YAP+ allele before migrating back to Africa.<ref name=\"altheide1997\"/> However some studies, such as Semino et al., indicate that the highest frequency and diversity of haplogroup E is in Africa, and East Africa is the most likely place of origin of the haplogroup.<ref name=\"semino\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Semino O, Magri C, Benuzzi G, Lin AA, Al-Zahery N, Battaglia V, Maccioni L, Triantaphyllidis C, Shen P, Oefner PJ, Zhivotovsky LA, King R, Torroni A, Cavalli-Sforza LL, Underhill PA, Santachiara-Benerecetti AS | title = Origin, diffusion, and differentiation of Y-chromosome haplogroups E and J: inferences on the neolithization of Europe and later migratory events in the Mediterranean area | journal = American Journal of Human Genetics | volume = 74 | issue = 5 | pages = 1023\u201334 | date = May 2004 | pmid = 15069642 | pmc = 1181965 | doi = 10.1086/386295 }}</ref>\n\nThe models supporting an African origin or an Asian origin of the YAP+ insertion both required the extinction of the ancestral YAP chromosome to explain the current distribution of the YAP+ polymorphism. Paragroup DE* possesses neither the mutations that define haplogroup D or haplogroup E. If paragroup DE* was found in one location but not the other, it would boost one theory over the other.<ref name=\"wells\">{{cite journal | vauthors = Wells RS, Yuldasheva N, Ruzibakiev R, Underhill PA, Evseeva I, Blue-Smith J, Jin L, Su B, Pitchappan R, Shanmugalakshmi S, Balakrishnan K, Read M, Pearson NM, Zerjal T, Webster MT, Zholoshvili I, Jamarjashvili E, Gambarov S, Nikbin B, Dostiev A, Aknazarov O, Zalloua P, Tsoy I, Kitaev M, Mirrakhimov M, Chariev A, Bodmer WF | title = The Eurasian heartland: a continental perspective on Y-chromosome diversity | journal = Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America | volume = 98 | issue = 18 | pages = 10244\u20139 | date = August 2001 | pmid = 11526236 | pmc = 56946 | doi = 10.1073/pnas.171305098 }}</ref> Haplogroup DE* has been found in [[Nigeria]],<ref name=weale/> [[Guinea-Bissau]]<ref name=\"rosa2007\"/> and also in [[Tibet]].<ref name=\"shi\" /> The phylogenetic relationship of three DE* sequences has yet to be determined, but it is known that the Guinea Bissau sequences differ from the Nigerian sequences by at least one mutation.<ref name=\"rosa2007\"/> Weale et al. state that the discovery of DE* among Nigerians pushes back the date for the [[most recent common ancestor]] (MRCA) of African YAP chromosomes. This, in his view, has the effect of reducing the time window through which a possible back migration from Asia to Africa could occur.<ref name=weale/>\n\nChandrasekhar et al. 2007,<ref>YAP insertion signature in South Asia - Chandrasekar 2007 (https://www.researchgate.net/publication/6053145_YAP_insertion_signature_in_South_Asia)</ref> have argued for an Asian origin of the YAP+. They state: \"The presence of the YAP insertion in Northeast Indian tribes and Andaman Islanders with haplogroup D suggests that some of the M168 chromosomes gave rise to the YAP insertion and M174 mutation in South Asia.\"\nThey also argue that YAP+ migrated back to Africa with other Eurasian haplogroups, such as [[haplogroup R1b (Y-DNA)|Haplogroup R1b1]]* (18-23kya), which has been observed with especially high frequency among the members of some peoples in northern [[Cameroon]], and [[Haplogroup T (Y-DNA)|Haplogroup T]] (39-45 kya), which has been observed in low frequencies in Africa. Haplogroup E at 50kya is considerably older than these haplogroups and has been observed at frequencies of 80-92% in Africa.\n\nIn a 2007 study, Peter Underhill and Toomas Kivisild stated that there will always be uncertainty regarding the precise origins of DNA sequence variants such as YAP because of a lack of knowledge concerning prehistoric demographics and population movements. However Underhill and Kivisild contend that with all the available information, the African origin of the YAP+ polymorphism is more parsimonious and more plausible than the Asian origin hypothesis.<ref name=\"underhill2007\" />\n\nIn a press release concerning a study by Karafet et al. 2008, Michael Hammer revised the dates for the origin Haplogroup DE from 55,000 years ago to 65,000 years ago. For haplogroup E, Hammer revised the dates from 31,000 years ago to 50,000 years ago. Hammer is also quoted as saying \u201cThe age of haplogroup DE is about 65,000 years, just a bit younger than the other major lineage to leave Africa, which is assumed to be about 70,000 years old\u201d, in which he implies that haplogroup DE left Africa soon after haplogroup CT.<ref>[http://genome.cshlp.org/site/press/Ychromohaplogroup.xhtml Scientists reshape Y chromosome haplogroup tree gaining new insights into human ancestry]</ref>\n\nA 2018 study, based on analyzing maternal and paternal markers, their current distribution, and inferences from the DNA of the Altai Neanderthals, supports an Asian origin of paternal haplogroup DE and maternal haplogroup L3. The study suggests a back migration into Africa and a following admixture of the native Africans with immigrating peoples from Asia. It is suggested that DE originated about 70,000 years ago somewhere near [[Tibet]] and [[Central Asia]]. Additionally, the authors argue that the presence of DE* in Tibet, and that Tibet shows the greatest diversity concerning haplogroup D, supports the origin of DE* in this region. It is further argued that haplogroup E is of Asian origin and that the haploid diversity of haplogroup E supports a strong Eurasian male gene flow. The authors conclude that this supports an Asian origin and may also explain signals of small percentages of Neanderthal DNA found in northern and some western Africans.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite journal|vauthors=Cabrera VM, Marrero P, Abu-Amero KK, Larruga JM|date=June 2018|title=Carriers of mitochondrial DNA macrohaplogroup L3 basal lineages migrated back to Africa from Asia around 70,000 years ago|journal=BMC Evolutionary Biology|volume=18|issue=1|pages=98|doi=10.1186/s12862-018-1211-4|pmc=6009813|pmid=29921229}}</ref>\n\nA 2019 study by Haber et al. supports an African origin for haplogroup DE*, based in part on the discovery of haplogroup D0 found in three Nigerians (according to the authors a branch of the DE lineage near the DE split but on the D branch), as well as on an analysis of y-chromosomal phylogeny, recently calculated haplogroup divergence dates and evidence for ancestral Eurasians outside Africa. The authors consider other possible scenarios, but conclude in favor of a model involving an African origin of hapologroup DE, with haplogroups E and D0 also originating in Africa, along with the migration out of Africa of the three lineages (C, D and FT) that now form the vast majority of non-African Y chromosomes. The authors find divergence times for DE*, E, and D0, all likely within a period of about 76,000-71,000 years ago, and a likely date for the exit of the ancestors of modern Eurasians out of Africa (and ensuing Neanderthal admixture) later around 50,300-59,400 years ago, which they argue, also supports an African origin for those haplogroups.<ref name=\"ReferenceC\"/>\n\n[[FTDNA]], in 2019, found three other D0 samples: one in Syria (the most basal sample of D0 found to date, diverging about 26,000 years ago), and two in Saudi Arabia. According to Runfeldt and Sager of FTDNA (as also found by Haber et al.), D0 is a very divergent offshoot on the D branch, diverging around 71,000 years ago, and lacking the M174 mutation that defines other D chromosomes. According to their schematics D0 can be grouped into an Asian cluster (West Asia) and African cluster (Nigeria). Two D0 branches were confirmed: D-FT75 found in West Asia and D-FT76 found in West Asia and West Africa. \"D0\" has also been alternately named \"D2\", and former D (D-M174) has now been termed \"D1\", since the discovery of D0. The research team says they will continue to analyze additional samples.<ref name=\"Estes\"/>\n\nBoth theories (Out-of-Africa and Out-of-Asia) regarding the origin of haplogroup DE are discussed and more studies are needed to conclude about a proposed origin.\n\n==Tree==\nBy ISOGG tree\uff08Version: 14.151\uff09.<ref>[https://docs.google.com/spreadsheets/d/1QBUFZl03X92qNN61lQ8VtIKwbBMeuBzvqXQ47IQPBps/edit#gid=437997455]</ref>\n\n*'''DE''' (YAP)\n**'''[[Haplogroup D (Y-DNA)|D]]''' (CTS3946)\n***'''D1''' (M174/Page30, IMS-JST021355, [[Haplogroup D-M174]])\n****'''D1a''' (CTS11577)\u3000\n*****'''[[Haplogroup D-Z27276|D1a1]]''' (F6251/Z27276)\n******'''D1a1a''' (M15)\u3000[[Tibet]]\n******'''D1a1b''' (P99)\u3000[[Tibet]], [[Mongol]], [[Central Asia]]\n*****'''[[Haplogroup D-M55|D1a2]]''' (M64.1/Page44.1, M55) \u3000 [[Japan]]\uff08[[Yamato people]]\u3001[[Ryukyuan people]]\u3001[[Ainu people]]\uff09\n*****'''D1a3''' (Y34637)\u3000[[Andaman Islands]]\uff08[[Onge people]]\u3001[[Jarawa (Andaman Islands)|Jarawa people]]\uff09\n****'''D1b''' (L1378) \u3000 [[Philippines]]<ref name = \"ISOGG2014\">[http://www.isogg.org/tree/ISOGG_HapgrpD.html Y-DNA Haplogroup D and its Subclades - 2014]</ref>\n***'''D2''' (A5580.2) \u3000[[Nigeria]], [[Saudi Arabia]], [[Syria]]\n\n{{Y-DNA}}\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Haplogroup D (Y-DNA)]]\n*[[Haplogroup E (Y-DNA)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Haplogroup DE of Y-DNA}}\n* Trombetta B. \"Phylogeographic Refinement and Large Scale Genotyping of Human Y Chromosome Haplogroup E Provide New Insights into the Dispersal of Early Pastoralists in the African Continent\" http://gbe.oxfordjournals.org/content/7/7/1940.long http://dienekes.blogspot.ru/2015/07/phylogeographic-refinement-of.html\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Haplogroup De (Y-Dna)}}\n[[Category:Human Y-DNA haplogroups|DE]]\n", "name_user": "Knuthove", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Undid revision 953861707 by95.245.36.118(talk) Unsourced, undiscussed, possible sock)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Haplogroup_DE"}
{"title_page": "1984 World Cup (men's golf)", "text_new": "{{use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox individual golf tournament\n| name          = 1984 World Cup\n| image         = \n| caption       = \n| dates         = 14\u201318 November\n| location      = [[Rome]], Lazio, Italy\n| coordinates   = \n| course        = [[Olgiata Golf Club]]<br>West Course\n| lang          = <!-- Defaults to US English. Value must be \"uk\" for British English -->\n| org           = \n| tour          = \n| format        = 54 holes [[stroke play]]<br>combined score\n| par           = 72\n| yardage       = {{convert|6999|yd|m}}\n| field         = 33 two-man teams\n| cut           = None\n| purse         = $150,000\n| winners_share = $60,000 team<br>$25,000 individual\n| champion      = {{ESP}}<br>[[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Ca\u00f1izares]] & [[Jos\u00e9 Rivero]]\n| score         = 414 (\u221218)\n| map           = \n| map_label     = \n| map_caption   = \n| map_relief =\n| map_label_position =\n| map_size =\n| previous      = [[1983 World Cup (men's golf)|1983]]\n| next          = [[1985 World Cup (men's golf)|1985]]\n}}\n{{Location map\n|Italy\n|relief     = 1\n|label      = <small>Olgiata</small>\n|lat        = 42.0377\n|long       = 12.3661\n|caption    = Location in [[Italy]]\n|position   = right\n|float      = \n|background = \n|width      = 240\n}}\nThe '''1984 World Cup''' took place 14\u201318 November at the Olgiata Golf Club, located 15 miles north of [[Rome]], [[Italy]]. It was the 31st [[World Cup (men's golf)|World Cup]] event. The tournament was a [[stroke play]] team event with 33 teams and was shortened from 72 holes to 54 holes, since the first day of play was cancelled, two hours after it started, due to heavy rain. Each team consisted of two players from a country. The combined score of each team determined the team results. The Spain team of [[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Ca\u00f1izares]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Rivero]] won by eight strokes over the  [[Taiwan]] team of  [[Chen Tze-chung|Chen Tse-chung]] and [[Hsieh Min-Nan|Hsieh Min-nan]].  It was the fourth Spanish victory in the last eight World Cup tournaments. The individual competition for The International Trophy, was won by Ca\u00f1izares two strokes ahead of [[Gordon Brand Jnr]], [[Scotland]]. Three players also competed as individuals: [[Roberto De Vicenzo]] of Argentina, [[Mohammed Said Moussa]] of Egypt, and [[John Jacobs (American golfer)|John Jacobs]] of the United States.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/335980251/?terms=%22World%2Bcup%22%2Bgolf |title=Rain threatens to delay the start of World Cup play |newspaper=The Tampa Tribune |location=Florida |date=15 November 1984 |page=6-C |via=newspaper.com |url-access=subscription}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |title=Ebel World of Professional Golf 1985 |first=Mark H. |last=McCormack |authorlink=Mark McCormack |publisher=Springwood Books |date=1985 |pages=406&ndash;408 |isbn=0862541247}}</ref>\n\n== Teams ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n!Country\n!Players\n|-\n|{{ARG}}\n|[[Vicente Fern\u00e1ndez (golfer)|Vicente Fern\u00e1ndez]] and [[Eduardo Romero]]\n|-\n|{{AUS}}\n|[[Mike Harwood]] and [[Paul Foley (golfer)|Paul Foley]]\n|-\n|{{AUT}}\n|[[Oswald Gartenmaier]] and [[Johannes Lamberg]]\n|-\n|{{BMU}}\n|[[Keith Smith (golfer)|Keith Smith]] and [[Kim Swan]]\n|-\n|{{BRA}}\n|[[Priscillo Diniz]] and [[Frederico German]]\n|-\n|{{CAN}}\n|[[Dave Barr (golfer)|Dave Barr]] and [[Jim Rutledge]]\n|-\n|{{COL}}\n|[[Rigoberto Velasquez]] and [[Alberto Rivadeneira]]\n|-\n|{{DNK}}\n|[[Per Greve]] and [[Hans Henrik Larsen]]\n|-\n|{{ENG}}\n|[[Howard Clark (golfer)|Howard Clark]] and [[Mark James (golfer)|Mark James]]\n|-\n|{{FRA}}\n|[[Michel Tapia]] and [[G\u00e9ry Watine]]\n|-\n|{{GRE}}\n|[[Bassili Karatzas]] and [[John Sotiropoulos]]\n|-\n|{{IND}}\n|[[Rohtas Singh (golfer)|Rohtas Singh]] and [[Brandon de Souza]]\n|-\n|{{IRL}}\n|[[Eamonn Darcy]] and [[Ronan Rafferty]]\n|-\n|{{ISL}}\n|[[Ragnar \u00d3lafsson]] (a) and [[Sigur\u00f0ur Pet\u00farsson]]\n|-\n|{{ITA}}\n|[[Delio Lovato]] and [[Silvano Locatelli]]\n|-\n|{{JAM}}\n|[[Seymour Rose]] and [[Wesley Scott]]\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|JPN|1947}}\n|[[Eitaro Deguchi]] and [[Namio Takasu]]\n|-\n|{{MYS}}\n|[[Marimuthu Ramayah]] and [[Sahabudin Yusoff]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pgatour.com/tournaments/world-cup-of-golf/news/2016/10/27/venezuela-s-vegas-brothers-head-to-melbourne-for-world-cup.html |title=Venezuela's Vegas brothers look to double down in Melbourne |publisher=PGA Tour |date=27 October 2016}}</ref>\n|-\n|{{MEX}}\n|[[Ramon Cruz]] and [[Enrique Serna (golfer)|Enrique Serna]]\n|-\n|{{NZL}}\n|[[Richard Coombes (golfer)|Richard Coombes]] and [[Ian Smalley]]\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|PRY|1990}}\n|[[Eladio Franco]] and [[Angel Jimenez (golfer)|Angel Jimenez]]\n|-\n|{{PHL}}\n|[[Paterno Braza]] and [[Mario Siodina]]\n|-\n|{{SCO}}\n|[[Gordon Brand Jnr]] and [[Sam Torrance]]\n|-\n|{{SIN}}\n|[[Lim Swee Wah]] and [[Lim Kiang Tiong]]\n|-\n|{{KOR}}\n|[[Lee Myung-ha]] and [[Choi Sang-ho]]\n|-\n|{{ESP}}\n|[[Jos\u00e9 Mar\u00eda Ca\u00f1izares]] and [[Jos\u00e9 Rivero]]\n|-\n|{{SWE}}\n|[[Anders Forsbrand]] and [[Magnus Persson (golfer)|Magnus Persson]]\n|-\n|{{TWN}}\n|[[Chen Tze-chung]] and [[Hsieh Min-Nan]]\n|-\n|{{THA}}\n|[[Somsak Srisanga]] and [[Uthai Thabpavibul]]\n|-\n|{{USA}}\n|[[Tom Kite]] and [[Lanny Wadkins]]\n|-\n|{{flagcountry|VEN|1930}}\n|[[Ramon Munoz (golfer)|Ramon Munoz]] and [[Julian Santana]]\n|-\n|{{WAL}}\n|[[Philip Parkin]] and [[Ian Woosnam]]\n|-\n|{{FRG}}\n|[[Karl-Heinz G\u00f6gele]] and [[Torsten Giedeon]]\n|}\n\n== Scores ==\n'''Team'''\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:95%;\"\n!#\n!Country\n!Score\n!To par\n!Money (US$)<br>(per team)\n|-\n|align=center|1 || {{ESP}} || 139-137-138=414 || align=center|\u221218 || align=center|60,000\n|-\n|rowspan=2 align=center|T2 || {{SCO}} || 136-142-144=422  || rowspan=2 align=center|\u221210 || rowspan=2 align=center|20,000\n|-\n|{{TWN}} || 137-148-137=422\n|-\n|rowspan=2 